<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 8 日星期二 11:58:03 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Who Speaks for the Trees?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>一个关于三棵树、愤怒的“社区”和华盛顿特区权力的故事<br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/C3iRoI6hkPEQlcPImgJS1xlo8hU=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/xenia_trees_2/original.jpg" alt="树根，上面画着地图和红点" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乔安妮·因佩里奥/《大西洋月刊》插图。资料来源：盖蒂；国会图书馆。</figcaption></figure> “<span class="smallcaps">这几乎就像是</span>政府将自己的意志强加于居民，”第 8 选区的华盛顿特区议员特雷恩·怀特 (Trayon White) 在该委员会 6 月 6 日的立法会议上表示。他说的不是拟议中的高速公路、地铁站、发电厂，或者——<em>打消这个想法</em>——公寓楼。他谈论的是树木：具体来说，是几年前华盛顿特区城市林业部门在 Xenia 街上种植的三棵椴树。令我惊讶的是，美国一个主要城市的立法机构正在经历<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/dc-md-va/2023/05/05/dc-homeless-annual-count/">无家可归者</a>不断升级和暴力<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://mpdc.dc.gov/page/district-crime-data-glance">犯罪</a>严重激增的情况，那天专门用了四分之一的时间来讨论三棵树。<br><br>怀特表示，他担心房地产价值的潜在风险，以及他认为“合理的担忧”，即一旦成熟，这些树木将“大到足以让人难以看清人行道及其周围的情况，这是一条公共道路”。安全问题。”他要求他的同事支持一项紧急决议，以便在这种情况发生之前将其移除。<br><br>有一段时间，成员们继续说，好像这对他们来说是一件完全正常的事情。一些人认为扩大树冠也许实际上是件好事。但没有人真正质疑怀特提议的基本前提：社区已经起来反对树木恐惧症。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2021/07/social-trees-meg-lowman-suzanne-simard/619015/">摘自 2021 年 7 月/8 月号：观察树木的更好方法</a><br><br>怀特说：“我们要指出的是，这些房主担心自己的房屋价值。” “我只是相信 [地区交通部 (DDOT)] 可以更友好地响应社区的需求，提出他们的要求，如果他们要求不同的树木，我不明白有什么大问题”。<br><br>委员会继续讨论公共安全问题的优点。议员肯尼·麦克杜菲回忆说，在他的选区内，市政府在停车位上种植了树木，以免侵占本已狭窄的人行道。 “我仍然质疑受影响社区是否有适当程度的协商和参与，”他表示支持怀特。<br><br> 20多分钟后，理事会主席惊讶地指出，“我们在移除三棵树的问题上花了这么多时间。”怀特认识到同事们缺乏足够的支持，因此将此事从议程中撤回，让树木再生长一天。<br><br>最初吸引我看到这个故事的是理事会会议上的言论与当前的主题之间明显不匹配。几棵树怎么会对公共安全或财产价值构成威胁？这些树是不是特别丑？<em>谁</em>是怀特推动将其移除的幕后黑手？就像许多关于政府的故事一样，这部看似微不足道的戏剧其实是关于权力，以及人们如何证明使用权力的合理性。<br><br> Xenia<span class="smallcaps">街</span>位于第 8 区，与华盛顿特区的大部分地区仅隔阿纳科斯蒂亚河 (Anacostia River)。这并不是它与众不同的唯一原因。河的这一边<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://censusreporter.org/profiles/61000US11008-ward-8-dc/">绝大多数是黑人</a>，与城市其他地区相比，失业率更高，劳动力参与率更低，贫困率更高。包含 Xenia 街的人口普查区是该市对热最敏感的区域之一，这一指标反映了哮喘、冠心病和残疾的患病率，以及种族和收入人口统计数据。华盛顿特区城市林业部（DDOT 的一个部门）在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aphis.usda.gov/aphis/resources/pests-diseases/hungry-pests/the-threat/emerald-ash-borer/emerald-ash-borer-beetle#:~:text=The%20Emerald%20Ash%20Borer%20(Agrilus,hidden%20in%20wood%20packing%20materials.">甲虫侵扰</a>损害了当地几棵白蜡树后种植了这些树木。一位高级官员告诉我，该部门普遍担心各区树冠分布不均：截至 6 月底，第 8 区收到了大约 500 个新种植的公开请求；收入较高的第四区有近 6,000 人。<br><br>植树不符合新道路或火车站可能需要的更严格类型的通知和社区输入流程的标准。但根据邻里咨询委员会前成员凯·阿姆斯特德（Kay Armstead）的说法，该委员会是一个选举产生的机构，旨在在分区、自行车道、酒类许可证等问题上发出超本地化的声音，该市确实向该委员会通报了一项计划，将在邻里种植更多树木。 2020 年秋季，该公司在两栋公寓楼（450 Xenia Street 和 450 Condon Terrace）之间的公共土地上种植了 35 棵树，其中一些是美国椴树，一些是苹果。<br><br>我想亲眼看看这些树。在怀特提出紧急决议后的几周内，我在三个不同的场合参观了这条安静的住宅街道，询问人们是否对这些树有任何想法。我采访过的人都没有表达强烈的意见，甚至没有听说过这场争议。<br><br> 450 Condon Terrace 的一位居民立即将我的注意力转移到她停车场地面上的一个大洞上，她说这是由一辆垃圾车造成的。另一位告诉我，他没有听说过这场争议，但想谈谈垃圾收集问题。 “我的意思是，看看这狗屎，”他指着人行道上的一堆垃圾说道。树？在优先事项列表中排名靠后。至少可以说，另一个人发现我的提问令人困惑。 “它们是氧气！”当我说有些人担心这些树会鼓励犯罪时，他嘲笑我。 “现在，你知道这太疯狂了。谁会躲在这些树下？”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/10/big-little-ideas-start-planting-trees/622142/">詹姆斯·法洛斯：开始植树</a><br><br>那么是谁组成了如此反对树木的“社区”呢？他的名字叫达里尔·罗斯。<br><br>几十年来，罗斯一直活跃于地方政治。他是第八选区民主党和怀特<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/dc-politics/just-a-quarter-of-dc-constituent-service-funds-provided-assistance-report-finds/2019/03/26/191d0f80-4fc8-11e9-88a1-ed346f0ec94f_story.html">选民服务基金</a>的财务主管，该基金是一个备受争议的钱包，一些批评者称其为“行贿基金”。当怀特提到选民就这个问题向他的办公室进行外展时，他指的是罗斯。 （怀特和他的幕僚长都拒绝接受本文的采访。）罗斯不住在 450 Xenia Street，但他以前住在 450 Xenia Street。他仍然拥有该大楼的一个单位，并将其出租，并且是 Xenia 公寓业主协会的主席。<br><br>从这些树被种植的那天起，罗斯就对它们感到愤怒。他告诉我，他看到工人在挖掘，并开始四处打电话，因为没有人向邻居通报该项目而感到愤怒，并惊讶于该市认为在街上种植 35 棵树（“一片森林！”）是有意义的；并对树木可能给居民带来的未来私人成本感到沮丧。<br><br>他提出的移除树木的 311 请求毫无结果。因此，他尝试了DDOT和城市林业部的官员、怀特和市议会的其他几位成员、监察长办公室以及邻里咨询委员会的现任和前任成员。他知道，如果没有人脉关系，他不可能获得如此多的关注：“相信我，我正在利用一切可能的手段来获得想要的结果，”他告诉我。<br><br>经过数月的努力，2021 年 8 月，怀特的幕僚长、DDOT 的代表和普通议员安妮塔·邦兹 (Anita Bonds) 的一名高级工作人员与罗斯和现场的几名地区居民会面，讨论了这个问题。官员们同意移除 35 棵新种植的树木中的 14 棵。该机构还承诺完成照明调查，安装了三盏大型路灯，这是一种<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://urbanlabs.uchicago.edu/projects/crime-lights-study">减少犯罪的数据驱动方法</a>。<br><br> “愿意为这个人妥协是因为我们想确保我们这样做是<em>为了</em>人民，而<em>不是</em>他们，”城市林业部门的一位高级官员（要求匿名）告诉我。 “如果我们能够安抚某人，产生一种主人翁意识……你就可以让某人成为你的盟友。”<br><br>罗斯并没有平静下来。他继续努力，又砍掉了三棵树——最靠近他的公寓大楼人行道的树。他向华盛顿特区监察长办公室提出投诉，DDOT 局长埃弗雷特·洛特 (Everett Lott) 做出了正式回应，他辩称，该部门在种植树木方面没有违反法律，实际上超出了公众通报的授权。罗斯没有被吓倒，继续他的倡导，最终怀特在六月的市议会会议上提出了紧急决议。<br><br>罗斯让我与他的一些盟友取得了联系，其中大多数人听起来只比我在访问中随机遇到的居民更了解情况。有些人不知道许多树木已经被砍伐；其他人只是模糊地意识到，在某一时刻，树木似乎是一个问题。一位女士告诉我，她认为孩子们可能会将掉落的苹果扔到汽车或建筑物窗户上。 （紧急立法中涉及的树木是椴树，而不是苹果。）<br><br>罗斯表示，公寓协会团结一致反对。他在我在场的情况下通过扬声器给副总统哈泽尔·法默打电话。<br><br> “你还记得有四棵[树]离人行道太近了吗？”他问。<br><br> “我以为我们已经完成了，”她说道，听起来很困惑。<br><br> “不不，我们还在战斗。”罗斯连忙回答道。<br><br>罗斯恢复记忆后，法默说，她担心有一天这些树会推高混凝土人行道，阻碍居民进出大楼。罗斯后来澄清说，法默已经搬出去了，因为人行道上的台阶对她来说太困难了。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">在 7 月的立法会议上，</span>怀特撤回了紧急决议，理由是 DC 理事会主席和 DDOT 达成妥协，对违规树苗使用生长调节剂。这一结果激怒了罗斯，他正在寻求与市长穆里尔·鲍泽会面：“最终我们投票给了她，我们没有投票给[DDOT官员]，我们相信她会做对社会最有利的事情。”人们。”<br><br>罗斯仍然有选择。如果最坏的情况发生，这些树最终延伸到人行道上，他可以拨打 311 请求修剪树木。据市林业局称，这些请求平均会在 20 天内得到解决。<br><br>但我与罗斯和他的盟友交谈得越多，我就越意识到这些树木也是他们对 DDOT 更广泛不满的替身，他们认为 DDOT 不是在<em>为</em>他们行事，而是在<em>对</em>他们做事：自行车架“刚刚掉在”了在一些企业面前，不顾他们的反对修建了自行车道，并在未经他们同意的情况<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.arcgis.com/apps/dashboards/a2f1cca5159e4c6eae197895d2e08336">下在华盛顿特区交通死亡率最高的病房</a>安装了交通安全基础设施。这就是罗斯能够首先通过利用一些居民对该市交通机构的现有愤怒来争取支持者的原因。愤怒的是，在近9万人的病房里，少数人没有说了算。<br><br>这是地方政府及其不满的经典故事。政府采取行动。愤怒的、人脉广泛的当地人士进行了反击，对没有征求他们的意见而感到恼火。但当他们反击并声称符合“人民”的意愿时，我们如何知道他们是否正确？稍微备份一下：我们如何决定这些<em>人是谁</em>？<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/07/local-government-power-nimby-denver/674164/">摘自2023年7月/8月号：科罗拉多州解决住房危机的巧妙想法</a><br><br>在《仙妮亚街》剧集中，是住在树旁边的人们吗？隔一条街怎么样？只是像罗斯这样的业主吗？因为树木位于公共土地上，所以所有特区居民都应该有发言权吗？都是美国人吗？解决<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.usda.gov/media/press-releases/2022/07/25/biden-harris-administration-announces-plans-reforestation-climate#:~:text=WASHINGTON%2C%20July%2025%2C%202022%20%E2%80%94,trees%20over%20the%20next%20decade.">重新造林积压问题是国家的首要任务</a>。或者，考虑到树木有助于缓解气候变化，<em>所有人都</em>应该有发言权吗？这就是所谓的边界问题，政治学家罗伯特·达尔曾调侃说，这个问题“没有理论解决方案”，只有务实的解决方案。即使调查全人类在理论上是可取的，但实际上也是不可能的。人们必须在某处划定界限并委派代表或发言人。<br><br>可以说，在这个问题上最好的代表是地方民选官员，他们从选民那里获得权力。问题在于，在地方层面，尤其是超地方层面，没有人投票。 2018年， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonblade.com/2018/08/17/two-thirds-of-d-c-neighborhood-races-uncontested/">三分之二的居委会竞选没有竞争</a>。即使这些竞赛竞争激烈，也只有少数人出席投票。在包括森尼亚街在内的单一议员选区，罗斯的盟友之一阿姆斯特德以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://electionresults.dcboe.org/election_results/2022-General-Election">137-91</a>落败。去年， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://dcist.com/story/22/12/01/two-dc-races-to-be-decided-by-casting-of-lots/">选举日后，非国大两场比赛打成平手</a>。在其中一项选举中，每位候选人均获得了 12 票，而在另一项选举中，每位候选人只获得了一张选票（大概是他们自己的）。确实是大众之声。<br><br>如果非国大不能完全代表人民，那么华盛顿特区议会，特别是议员怀特呢？市议会的投票率也很低： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://data.census.gov/table?q=B29001:+CITIZEN,+VOTING-AGE+POPULATION+BY+AGE&amp;g=040XX00US11%246100000_1400000US11001000101&amp;tid=ACSDT5Y2021.B29001">在第 8 选区约 57,000 名达到投票年龄的公民</a>中，约有 8,700 人在确保怀特连任的 2020 年初选中投票。<br><br> DDOT 怎么样？作为行政部门的一个机构，DDOT 的权力来自市长。 2022 年，鲍泽市长在初选（这座民主党占主导地位的城市的真正选举）期间从第 8 选区获得了不到 4,000 张选票。该选区只有约 10,000 人在这次竞选中投票。<br><br>民选官员在民主上合法化并不存在什么神奇的门槛。但超过一半的合格选民<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.census.gov/newsroom/press-releases/2023/2022-voting-registration.html#:~:text=Turnout%20rates%20for%20the%20citizen,%25)%20citizen%20voting%2Dage%20population.">通常都会参加</a>联邦和州的竞选，而我们的市政选举<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://www.whovotesformayor.org/">却很难争取到 15% 的选票</a>。我们在地方政府中看到的是其他级别政府无与伦比的民主危机。<br><br> “我<span class="smallcaps">不是树木，而是树木。”</span>这是不尊重，”阿姆斯特德告诉我。她称砍伐树木是首要任务，因为“当你来到一个社区而不倾听时，[我们]就会受到不尊重和忽视。”罗斯也提出了类似的观点：“这让我很生气，因为就像我说的，我们是利益相关者。我们是纳税人。我们为华盛顿特区政府雇员、议会提供工资......这是我们的钱！”<br><br>当我们集体认为有权让政府承担责任时，那就是民主。但当个人这样做时，那就是另一回事了：制度俘获。<br><br>由于很少有人在地方选举中投票，那些敢于发声并声称代表社区发言的人的力量很难受到挑战。如果以邻里爱管闲事的人为首的房主协会说他代表你说话，你会出现对这种说法提出异议吗？罗斯的毅力显而易见，其有效性很大程度上归功于其独特性。如果<em>每个人</em>都像他一样参与，打电话、发电子邮件、参加一次又一次的会议，向监察长办公室自下而上的每个人提出投诉，他的权力就会立即被削弱。如果每个人都为自己说话，那么没有人可以声称代表社区说话。<br><br>民主是关于反馈循环的。我们选举人。如果他们做得不好，我们就会选择替代方案。但当选举制度因废弃而动摇时，其他反馈循环就会生根发芽。地方一级的民选官员要对极少数参与其中但不具代表性的选民负责；公务员对人脉广泛的人变得先发敏感，因为他们有时间和精力要求过度关注。<br><br>像罗斯这样的人可能无法得到他们想要的一切，但他们知道如何吸引注意力。不少于四名 DC 议员亲自参与了 Xenia 街树木问题。与此同时，地面上那个巨大的洞？它还在那里。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trees-xenia-street-washington-dc-local-government/674949/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trees-xenia-street-washington-dc-local-government/674949/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Killer Apps]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>社交媒体是否让美国的谋杀案激增变得更糟？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/BsZBNpGQ7buWlTQSboDFdaRRL8Q=/258x0:1259x1251/648x810/media/img/2023/08/01/DIS_McGillis_InstaViolence/original.jpg" alt="一只手指着一把枪口形状像 Instagram 标志的枪" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>埃里克·卡特插图</figcaption></figure><span class="smallcaps">2020 年的一个秋天晚上</span>，贾雷尔·杰克逊 (Jarell Jackson) 和沙贾汉·麦卡斯基尔 (Shahjahan McCaskill) 正在杰克逊的现代索纳塔 (Hyundai Sonata) 中聊天， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.inquirer.com/news/west-philadelphia-shootings-homicide-rates-instagram-feuds-20210316.html">当时还处于假期后的兴奋状态，突然 24 颗子弹射穿了汽车</a>。这两个人都是 26 岁，从学前班起就是亲密的朋友。他们在波多黎各玩了几天悬挂式滑翔、滑索和徒步旅行后刚刚返回西费城。杰克逊把车停在他妈妈的房子外面，这时一辆黑色SUV停了下来，车内的人开始开枪。他和麦卡斯基尔均在医院被宣布死亡。<br><br>事后，麦卡斯基尔的母亲纳吉拉·扎伊纳布·阿里·麦卡斯基尔无法理解为什么有人想要杀死她的儿子和他的朋友。两人都战胜了附近年轻黑人的困境，并从大学毕业。杰克逊曾是青少年精神病房的心理健康技术员，而她的儿子则经营一家小型清洁公司并经营酒吧。她想知道他们是否是一名心怀不满的清洁公司前雇员的目标。但随后警方解释说：她的儿子和他的朋友因社交媒体上一些从未谋面的青少年之间发生冲突而被杀。<br><br>几个月来，市场街两边的工作人员在 Instagram 上展开了一场激烈的战斗。他们之间的竞争由来已久，但网上一连串的嘲讽和威胁加剧了社区的紧张气氛。警方已指派一名警官监视该市各个人员的社交媒体活动，该部门怀疑SUV中的北边人将这两个朋友中的一个误认为是竞争对手南边人并开枪。枪击事件发生一小时后，一名北区人在 Instagram 上发布了一张照片，其标题似乎是在嘲笑受害者，并鼓励对手的工作人员来收集他们的尸体：“啊哈啊，猫把他们捡起来！！”<br><br>杰克逊和麦卡斯基尔在全国暴力活动死灰复燃的第一年去世，这场暴力活动抹去了二十多年来公共安全方面取得的成果。 2020 年，凶杀案激增 30%，并在接下来的两年里围绕该水平波动。有<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/us-murder-rate-decline-crime-statistics/674290/">初步迹象</a>表明，2023 年的比率可能会比去年下降 10% 以上，但这仍将远高于大流行前的水平。<br><br>犯罪学家指出了多种因素的综合作用，包括 COVID-19 造成的社会混乱、大流行初期枪支销售的增加，以及乔治·弗洛伊德被谋杀后的骚动，这在许多城市导致警察活动减少和对警察的信任进一步受到侵蚀。但在我对这一激增的报道中，我不断听到另一个促进因素：社交媒体。<br><br>暴力预防工作人员描述了从 Instagram、Snapchat 和其他平台开始的争斗，并以惊人的速度爆发到现实生活中。 “当我年轻的时候，我会在学校与某人发生争执，唯一知道这件事的人就是我和学校里的人，”巴尔的摩的暴力预防工作者詹姆斯·廷普森说。 “不是现在。在你离开学校之前，就有五百人知道了。然后一场大战就开始了。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2022/04/american-teens-sadness-depression-anxiety/629524/">阅读：为什么美国青少年如此悲伤</a><br><br>智能手机和社交平台早在凶杀案激增之前就已存在。它们显然不是其唯一原因。但考虑到最近的过去，就不难看出为什么社交媒体可能成为新的暴力暴力驱动因素。当疫情导致官员关闭学校、图书馆和娱乐中心等市政中心一年多时，人们——尤其是年轻人——被进一步推入虚拟空间。关于大量使用社交媒体与青少年心理健康问题和自杀之间可能存在的联系，人们已经讨论了很多。现在，廷普森和其他暴力预防工作者正在将这种担忧带入合乎逻辑的下一步。如果社交媒体在年轻人伤害自己的倾向上升中发挥了作用，那么当他们伤害他人时，它是否也会发挥作用呢？<br><br>目前暴力事件的激增并不是谋杀率回到了 90 年代，而是完全不同的情况。在许多城市，暴力尤其集中在年轻人中。从 2014 年到 2021 年，全国 15 至 19 岁青少年的凶杀率 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/products/databriefs/db471.htm">惊人地增加了 91%。</a>去年，华盛顿特区<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/dc-md-va/2022/12/31/homicides-dc-va-md-2022/">有 105 名 18 岁以下青少年被枪杀</a>，几乎是前一年的两倍。 2022 年前 9 个月，费城青少年枪击受害者人数为 181 人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/local/philadelphia/2022/10/05/philadelphia-gun-violence-youth-victims">，相当于 2015 年和 2016 年全年的总人数</a>。在巴尔的摩，今年上半年已有 60 多名 13 至 18 岁的儿童遭到枪杀。这是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thebaltimorebanner.com/community/criminal-justice/teen-shootings-gun-violence-baltimore-UW47CTUZVVFCZDMHUVZOY3WGJQ/">2015 年至 2021 年上半年凶杀案总数的两倍</a>，而且发生在该市凶杀案总体下降的时期。在全国范围内，这种趋势在种族上已经达到了极端程度：2021年，10岁至24岁的黑人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://stacks.cdc.gov/view/cdc/121555">成为凶杀案受害者的可能性几乎是年轻白人的14倍</a>。<br><br>那些面对这一祸害的人——警察、检察官、干预人员——坚信社交媒体的煽动有助于解释为什么今天的年轻人在受害者中所占比例更大。但他们不知道如何应对这种现象。他们明白这波新的杀戮浪潮需要新的解决方案——但它们是什么？<br><br><span class="smallcaps">就网络煽动引起关注的程度而言</span>，它主要集中在说唱视频，特别是那些以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vulture.com/article/jayquan-mckenley-chii-wvtzz-eric-adams-drill.html#_ga=2.8250674.1462920847.1690910851-270587328.1687895713">练习音乐</a>为特色的视频，该视频于 2010 年代初在芝加哥开始，以明确地引诱“opps”或竞争对手为主导。这些视频与多起枪击事件有关。不过，冲突通常是由更平凡的在线活动引发的。青少年在 Instagram 帖子中引诱竞争对手，或者在私人聊天中受到盟友的刺激。在 Instagram 和 Facebook 上，他们直播入侵敌方领土的情况，并面临“放下大头针”的挑战——暴露自己的位置，否则就会被视为胆小鬼。他们在 Snapchat 照片或 YouTube 和 TikTok 视频中挥舞枪支，这可能会激起对手的回应，并迫使持枪者实际使用它。<br><br> “如果你不监控社交媒体，你就会想知道为什么 1000 人突然在市中心打架。”<br><br> 12 月，我在宾夕法尼亚州胡茨代尔的州立监狱见到了 21 岁的布兰登·奥利维耶里 (Brandon Olivieri)，他因谋杀罪正在监狱服刑。奥利维耶里说，2017 年，他试图在费城南部的其他青少年的地盘上出售大麻，结果与他们发生了冲突。后来，在奥利维耶里和他的朋友们的 Instagram 私人聊天中，有人发布了一张银色 0.45 口径手枪的照片。然后另一名成员尼古拉斯·托雷利(Nicholas Torelli)在人行道上贴出了一张猫粪便的照片，并配上标题“布兰登在对方领地拉了屎。”这是一个玩笑，但谈话很快就变得咄咄逼人。那天晚些时候，奥利维耶里要求托雷利将对手的照片放到聊天中，这样每个人都可以看到他们的样子。托雷利照做了，根据法庭记录，奥利维耶里回答说他会“把他们全部杀掉”。<br><br>当月晚些时候，奥利维耶里、托雷利和两个朋友遇到了他们的四个对手，双方发生了激烈的争吵、打斗以及银手枪中的三声枪响。奥利维耶里小组的成员卡利尔·米勒 (Caleer Miller) 被一颗子弹击中。另一名船员中的萨尔瓦托·迪努比勒 (Salvatore DiNubile) 也被击中。两人都死了；他们当时 16 岁。奥利维耶里因迪努比勒之死而被判一级谋杀罪，因米勒之死而被判三级谋杀罪。 （托雷利作证指控奥利维耶里，但没有受到指控。）奥利维耶里被判处 37 年至无期徒刑。<br><br> DiNubile 的父亲也叫 Salvatore，他认为在线分享威胁的能力鼓励了奥利维耶里和他的朋友们制造威胁；完成这些任务后，他们感到有必要坚持到底。 “你说过你要对付这个家伙。这是你的机会，”他告诉我。 “你试图辜负他自创的黑帮心态。”奥利维耶里坚称自己是清白的，并表示自己不是开枪的人，但他也同意，他和他的朋友经常在网上吹牛来互相炒作。 “这就是我们所说的造假，”他解释道。<br><br><span class="smallcaps">去年，</span>随着华盛顿特区的青少年枪击受害者人数攀升至三位数，该市负责培训社区成员预防暴力的和平学院举办了一场专门针对社交媒体的 Zoom 会议。华盛顿特区总检察长办公室的阿明·比尔 (Ameen Beale) 分享了他的屏幕，展示了典型的网络冲突最终导致死亡的场景。<br><br>演示以一张 2019 年发布在 Instagram 上的照片开始，照片中当地说唱歌手 AhkDaClicka 在地铁上；标题嘲笑他在没有枪的情况下被对手抓住。随后出现了 AhkDaClicka 和竞争对手说唱歌手 Walkdown Will 之间的私人消息截图，后者在 Instagram Live 上嘲讽地发布了该消息。接下来，AhkDaClicka 的 Instagram 故事侮辱了另一名据称参加地铁冲突的说唱歌手，以及 AhkDaClicka<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PFxpUO0J9E4">讲述这一事件</a>的 YouTube 视频，其中包括“给我一把格洛克，给我指点一下对手”这句台词。不久之后，即 2020 年 1 月，AhkDaClicka 被枪杀。他18岁；他的真名是马利克·西塞。那年 5 月，警方逮捕了同为 18 岁的 Walkdown Will—William Whitaker。去年 10 月，他承认犯有二级谋杀罪。<br><br>比尔的演讲让一些与会者目瞪口呆。 “我不敢相信这种不成熟和愚蠢的程度已经成为常态，”一位网友在聊天中写道。另一位提出了会议期间迫在眉睫的问题：该市预防暴力领域是否有人要求社交媒体公司限制煽动性内容？<br><br> “我认为我们没有取得太大进展，”比尔承认。他说，当市政府寻求删除帖子时，这些公司以有关言论自由的模糊论点拒绝了其请求。即使社交媒体平台确实删除了某个帖子，也可能已经有 20 个人与数百或数千人分享了该帖子。考虑到在线生活的节奏，您可能会花五年时间尝试阻止一个平台上的有害内容，结果所有活动都迁移到另一个平台。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/social-media-teen-mental-health-crisis-research-limitations/674371/">阅读：没有人确切知道社交媒体对青少年做了什么</a><br><br>我向拥有 YouTube 的谷歌发言人询问了关于 AhkDaClicka 视频（其中包含有关 Glock 的台词）以及去年夏天发布的另一则视频（标题为“Pull Da Plug”）的情况。照片中，肯塔基州路易斯维尔的一名说唱歌手和其他大约十几名年轻人显然正在庆祝一场枪击事件，这场枪击事件导致一名男子依靠生命维持系统（后来他去世了）。路易斯维尔暴力预防机构的负责人告诉我，受害者的家人要求谷歌删除该视频，但该视频并未删除，观看次数超过 15,000 次。发言人杰克·马龙告诉我，该公司通常有一个“相当高的门槛”来确定音乐视频煽动暴力，部分原因是公司政策<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://support.google.com/youtube/answer/2802268#zippy=%2Cother-types-of-content-that-violate-this-policy">允许艺术内容例外</a>。<br><br>我与 Malon 以及他在 Snap 和 Meta（拥有 Facebook 和 Instagram）的同行的谈话给我留下的印象是，与更引人注目的辩论相比，社交媒体平台相对较少考虑它们在助长常规枪支暴力方面的作用。审查煽动性政治言论。 Meta 向我指出了它的“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://transparency.fb.com/en-gb/policies/community-standards">社区标准</a>”，其中充满了灰色地带的声明，例如“我们还尝试考虑语言和上下文，以便将随意的声明与对公共或个人安全构成可信威胁的内容区分开来。” Snap 辩称，它的平台比其他平台更加良性，因为帖子的设计目的是消失，并且主要由朋友查看。我也联系了 TikTok，但该公司没有回应。<br><br>与此同时，社区只能自力更生。但预防暴力团体主要由成长于智能手机时代之前的中年男性主导。他们更愿意亲自干预，而不是解读 TikTok 上的威胁。在大流行之前，匹兹堡主要反暴力组织的一名实习生扫描了被认为有卷入冲突风险的年轻人在社交媒体上发布的帖子。市政府与暴力预防组织的联络人康奈尔·琼斯牧师告诉我，实习生曾经发现青少年之间正在网上酝酿一场争斗，其中一些人获得了枪支。琼斯带了参与者和他们的母亲来，化解了局势。然后，实习生离开小镇去法学院学习，该组织又恢复了对此类团体来说更典型的临时方法。 “如果你不监控社交媒体，你就会想知道为什么 1,000 人突然在市中心打架，”琼斯悲伤地说道。 7月初，巴尔的摩一个街区派对上发生的枪击事件证实了他的担忧：尽管该事件在社交媒体上被广泛讨论，但现场并没有警察；后来，一段视频流传，一名青少年在聚会上炫耀一把疑似枪支的东西。枪击事件造成两人死亡、28 人受伤。<br><br>十年前，宾夕法尼亚大学社会政策、传播学和精神病学教授德斯蒙德·厄普顿·巴顿 (Desmond Upton Patton) 获得了第一笔拨款，用于研究他所谓的“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0747563212003779">互联网攻击</a>”。他的研究团队与哥伦比亚大学的一个团队共同设计了算法，用于分析 Twitter 上的语言、图像甚至表情符号，并识别有伤害自己或他人风险的用户。这些算法在识别不断升级的在线纠纷方面显示出了希望。但他从未允许使用它们，担心它们与警方的监视工作相似，后者只能进行侧写而不是预防。 “也许有一个更聪明的人能够弄清楚如何合乎道德地做到这一点，”他对我说。<br><br>目前，该系统无法预测暴力行为，甚至经常无法对社交媒体上指控其有罪的人定罪。五月，三名青少年因谋杀贾雷尔·杰克逊和沙贾汉·麦卡斯基尔而在费城受审。枪击发生时，两人 17 岁，第三人 16 岁。社交媒体活动构成了检察官证据的关键部分：Instagram 帖子和视频显示，三名被告驾驶着一辆与那辆看似一模一样的黑色 SUV那辆车停在杰克逊的车旁边。其他帖子显示，其中两人持有一把与枪击事件中使用的描述相符的枪。经过一天的审议，陪审团宣判他们无谋杀罪，并裁定其中两名被告仅犯有武器罪。这一判决让受害者家属感到震惊。 “对于我和我的家人来说，[审判]就像一场为期 7 天的葬礼，”贾雷尔的母亲莫妮克·杰克逊告诉我。后来，调查谋杀案的侦探向她推测，此类案件的陪审员往往很难掌握社交媒体的基本机制以及它对年轻人互动的重要性。正如巴顿对我所说的那样，“我们一次又一次地低估了社交媒体与现实生活的区别。这<i>就是</i>生活。”<br><br> <em><small>This article has been updated to clarify YouTube&#39;s policy for determining which videos are removed for inciting violence.</small></em><br><br> <small><em>This article is a collaboration between</em> The Atlantic <em>and ProPublica. It appears in the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/toc/2023/09">September 2023</a> print edition with the headline “Killer Apps.”</em></small><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/jarell-jackson-shahjahan-mccaskill-killed-philadelphia-social-media/674760/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/jarell-jackson-shahjahan-mccaskill-killed-philadelphia-social-media/674760/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Mike Pence’s 11th Commandment]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Thou may speak ill of Trump, but carefully. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/cTTxI1FB31U4Xhlmi-d3uh0WYyc=/0x0:5693x3202/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/GettyImages_1552040644/original.jpg" alt="迈克·彭斯在舞台上" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Anna Moneymaker / Getty</figcaption></figure> <small><i>This is an edition of</i> The Atlantic <i>Daily, a newsletter that guides you through the biggest stories of the day, helps you discover new ideas, and recommends the best in culture.</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>Sign up for it here.</i></a></small><br><br> Ronald Reagan&#39;s 11th commandment was: “Thou shalt not speak ill of any fellow Republican.” This weekend, Mike Pence—like most of the GOP field—struggled mightily to criticize Donald Trump while barely mentioning Trump&#39;s name.<br><br> First, here are three new stories from <i>The Atlantic</i> :<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/08/black-folk-book-working-class-blair-lm-kelley/674935/">Ibram X. Kendi: <i>Working class</i> does not equal <i>white</i> .</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trumps-unhinged-attacks-smith-and-chutkan/674945/">Trump is acting like he&#39;s cornered</a> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trumps-unhinged-attacks-smith-and-chutkan/674945/">.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/addiction-drug-policy-language-harm-evidence/674907/">The burden of proof is on the language police.</a></li> <strong>Scared to Say His Name</strong><br><br> Let us remind ourselves to speak well of Mike Pence for one moment. Not only did he do his constitutional duty on January 6, 2021, thereby averting the collapse of the US government and the bloodshed that likely would have followed, but lately he seems to be exerting visible caloric effort to criticize the man he served as vice president. And yet, like so many other leading Republicans, Pence seems to be under a kind of necromancer&#39;s curse in which he risks being struck dumb when trying to say Donald Trump&#39;s name.<br><br> Yesterday, the CBS correspondent Major Garrett <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mike-pence-face-the-nation-aug-6-2023-transcript/">asked Pence</a> whether he&#39;d still vote for Trump. It was an opportunity to knock a softball out of the park. Instead, he flailed.<br><br><p> <b>Major Garrett:</b> Would you ever vote again for Donald Trump?</p><p> <b>Mike Pence:</b> Look, I don&#39;t think I&#39;ll have to. I have to tell you, everywhere I go—</p><p> <b>Garrett:</b> That wasn&#39;t the question, Mr. Vice President. Would you ever vote for Donald Trump again?</p><p> <b>Pence:</b> Yeah. Yeah, I know what your question is, but let me be very clear: I&#39;m running for president because I don&#39;t think anyone who ever puts himself over the Constitution should ever be president or should ever be president again.</p> Well, that&#39;s one way to go. Another would be to say, “I know from personal experience that Donald Trump is the most dangerous man ever to sit in the Oval Office, and I will do everything I can to stop him.” To his (again, very small) credit, Pence did open the interview by using Trump&#39;s name long enough to say that he was “wrong” on January 6. Trump, Pence said, “asked me to put him over the Constitution that day, but I chose the Constitution and I always will.” When asked if he would testify against Trump, Pence again whimpered: “I have no plans to testify, but people can be confident we&#39;ll—we&#39;ll obey the law. We&#39;ll respond to the call of the law, if it comes, and we&#39;ll just tell the truth.”<br><br> This is not exactly breathtaking defiance. Nor should we be overly impressed by an American politician affirming that he would honor an oath to the Constitution he&#39;s repeatedly taken in the past. But in these strange times, we take what we can get. Still, Pence was clearly uncomfortable with the question and did everything he could to leave Trump&#39;s name out of the discussion, which is an odd thing to do when you&#39;re heading a campaign against your own former running mate.<br><br> Likewise, consider Ron DeSantis&#39;s grudging acceptance that Trump lost the 2020 election. “Of course he lost,” DeSantis said in an <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/meet-the-press/video/-of-course-he-lost-ron-desantis-rejects-trump-s-2020-election-claims-190139973789">interview</a> with NBC News today. “Joe Biden&#39;s the president.” And Trump&#39;s lies about the election? “Unsubstantiated,” the Florida governor <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/04/us/politics/desantis-trump-election-2020.html">said on Friday</a> . DeSantis has been <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2024-election/ron-desantis-of-course-trump-lost-2020-election-rcna98200">insistent</a> that the 2024 election should be about Joe Biden, but he seems unwilling to deal with the reality that taking on Biden requires defeating Trump first. A <i>New York Times</i> report<i> </i><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/07/us/politics/desantis-trump-2020-election.html">referred</a> to the NBC comments as “Mr. DeSantis&#39;s increasingly aggressive stance,” which I suppose is true if you think of the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2023/07/19/desantis-jan-6-trump/">move from “nothing” to “something”</a> as “increasingly aggressive.”<br><br> Why are Republicans so scared to mention Trump, even at this late date? There are three reasons, two of them grounded in sheer cowardice and the third derived from a hallucinatory primary strategy.<br><br> The first and most obvious problem for GOP candidates is that barking back at Trump infuriates the Republican base, many of whom live in districts and states that Republicans care about. Chris Christie and Asa Hutchinson are willing to go after Trump because they are both men with thick skin—but also because they have almost no chance of gaining the GOP nomination. George Will <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.yahoo.com/george-republican-party-living-fear-182154354.html?guccounter=1&amp;guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&amp;guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAFshqvzmYCDZvo-PSldHCEUCkXZoCz5GQ9F4OUpI7GFYNPMB0Hv2yWkYzZw8liIlhcrnqdXhB55EmYrN8J_o--wzM26iKsfIhVmDy9VloPQqJHz5v7NSirjb-hVeB5QgSshUsswyNWgNhFai3OCiOOPhywR-0IlhUDtVQpFsrLyx">said it first</a> , but it bears repeating: The modern GOP is the first American party that fears its own voters.<br><br> Few candidates want to cross Trump and then endure his vicious attacks, which is understandable but hardly an example of leadership. (Trump has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.com/news/2023/08/05/trump-pence-has-gone-to-the-dark-side-00109960">already blasted</a> “Liddle&#39; [ <i>sic</i> ] Mike Pence” on his social-media platform, Truth Social, accusing him of being an ungrateful loser who has “gone to the Dark Side.”) And although too many Americans are no longer shocked by it, Trump&#39;s attacks create <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/threats-follow-trump-poliical-attacks/2020/10/28/c6dbce02-1792-11eb-82db-60b15c874105_story.html">real problems of security</a> when he zeroes in on his perceived enemies: Look at how much effort New York; Washington, DC; and, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2023/07/31/georgia-2020-election-investigation-trump/">apparently, Atlanta</a> have had to undertake just to indict or prepare to indict Trump.<br><br> Even on a less dire level, however, no one running for president—or trying to hold together what&#39;s left of the Republican Party—needs the headache of a brainless brawl with Trump. From DeSantis and Pence on down, the GOP field avoids invoking Trump&#39;s name, treating him (as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/peacefield/61a69df40b037b002073ccd5/fight-like-adults/">I wrote in 2021</a> ) as if he were some sort of ancient god or mystical <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://en.natmus.dk/historical-knowledge/denmark/middle-ages-1000-1536/j-r-r-tolkien/balrog-medieval-monsters/">Balrog</a> who will appear and unleash chaos at the mention of his name.<br><br> Finally, the GOP primary candidates seem to share a vanity-driven belief that each of them could inherit Trump&#39;s voters once Trump is out of the race because of his legal troubles, or when some other act of God takes him off the board. Somewhere, there&#39;s a strategist telling his client that <i>but for Trump</i> ,<i> </i>voters would stampede toward, say, Nikki Haley or Vivek Ramaswamy. This is what the <i>Bulwark</i> writer Tim Miller has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thetriad.thebulwark.com/p/ron-desantiss-prisoners-dilemma">called</a> “a fantasy primary,” the one being held inside the heads of “Republican elites who secretly loathe Trump and are hoping that voters will soon come to their senses” and pick someone else.<br><br> Now, it&#39;s true that if Trump were physically incapacitated—and I do not wish any ill health on the former president—then, yes, Republicans would have to find someone else. Short of that, however, Trump is clearly going to run even if he is incarcerated. (No <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2021/05/can-trump-run-for-president-from-prison.html">law or constitutional rule</a> prevents such an attempt.) He will continue to attack American institutions, and he will go on making barely veiled threats of violence, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2023/03/23/indictment-looms-trump-criticizes-calls-peace/">as he has done repeatedly</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/legal/trumps-threatening-post-flagged-by-us-prosecutors-judge-2023-08-05/">even while under indictment</a> .<br><br> Meanwhile, other Republicans are unable to say Trump&#39;s name, press the case against him as unfit for office, or make any of his alleged criminal activity relevant to GOP voters. Back in March, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/03/mike-pence-trump-january-6/673402/">I wrote</a> that Pence “had his one moment of courage, and there will be no others.” Unfortunately, I was right. At this point, other Republicans will head into 2024 unable to mimic even Pence&#39;s sole day of decency.<br><br> <b>Related:</b><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/03/mike-pence-trump-january-6/673402/">Mike Pence is warning us about Trump.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/trump-2024-election-lead-lincoln-dinner/674877/">Trump&#39;s inevitability problem</a></li> <strong>Today&#39;s News</strong><br><br><li> Tou Thao, a former police officer convicted for his role in the killing of George Floyd, <a href="https://apnews.com/article/george-floyd-minneapolis-officer-tou-thou-sentencing-586deaeb4d14807ef3f2bdd0196d0b86">was sentenced</a> to almost five years in prison by a state court.</li><li> Ukraine claims that it <a href="https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/zelenskyy-assassination-plot-ukraine-detains-russia-informant-rcna98507">has detained</a> a Russian informant who it says was part of an apparent plot to assassinate President Volodymyr Zelensky via air strike.</li><li> City officials in Juneau, Alaska, <a href="https://www.axios.com/2023/08/07/record-glacial-flooding-juneau-alaska-emergency-declaration">declared an emergency</a> yesterday because of record glacial lake flooding that destroyed at least two buildings.</li> <b>Evening Read</b><br><br> The Weaponization of Loneliness<br><br> <em>By Hillary Rodham Clinton</em><br><br><p> The question that preoccupied me and many others over much of the past eight years is how our democracy became so susceptible to a would-be strongman and demagogue. The question that keeps me up at night now—with increasing urgency as 2024 approaches—is whether we have done enough to rebuild our defenses or whether our democracy is still highly vulnerable to attack and subversion.</p><p> There&#39;s reason for concern: the influence of dark money and corporate power, right-wing propaganda and misinformation, malign foreign interference in our elections, and the vociferous backlash against social progress. The “vast right-wing conspiracy” has been of compelling interest to me for many years. But I&#39;ve long thought something important was missing from our national conversation about threats to our democracy. Now recent findings from a perhaps unexpected source—America&#39;s top doctor—offer a new perspective on our problems and valuable insights into how we can begin healing our ailing nation.</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/hillary-clinton-essay-loneliness-epidemic/674921/">Read the full article.</a><br><br> <b>More From <em>The Atlantic</em></b><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/freedom-to-read-pen-america-censorship/674936/">The three attacks on intellectual freedom</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/ai-chatgpt-college-essay-plagiarism/674928/">Here comes the second year of AI college.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/viktor-orban-illiberalism-ron-desantis-universities/674915/">Why the populist right hates universities</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/electric-vehicle-energy-infrastructure-heat-waves/674940/">Texas is a look into the future of driving.</a></li> <strong>Culture Break</strong><br><br> <b>Read.</b> In an age of distraction, here are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/08/attention-focus-book-recommendations/674941/">seven books</a> that will make you put down your phone.<br><br> <b>Watch.</b><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.amazon.com/Im-A-Virgo-Season-1/dp/B0B8PXXV2M"><i>I&#39;m a Virgo</i></a><i> </i>(streaming on Amazon Prime Video) is <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/boots-riley-virgo-show-recommendation/674933/">a sweet, surrealist coming-of-age series</a> that follows a 13-foot-tall Black man who is kept hidden by his family until he finally escapes.<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">Play our daily crossword.</a><br><br><b>聚苯乙烯</b><br><br>When you work for a magazine, people send you stuff, such as announcements of presidential campaigns. This is how I know that Steve Laffey is running for president.<br><br> I note with local pride that Laffey is the former mayor of Cranston, Rhode Island, a city not too far away from where I live in the Ocean State. (I have never met him; it&#39;s not <i>that</i> small a state.) He served one term as mayor, ran for the US Senate in 2006, and lost. He almost ran for Rhode Island governor in 2010; instead he moved to Colorado, got into the governor&#39;s race there in 2013, pulled out of that one, and then tried to get the GOP nomination in Colorado&#39;s Fourth Congressional District in 2014 (and lost).<br><br> I wasn&#39;t paying much attention to local politics back then, so I can&#39;t really judge whether Laffey was any good as a mayor. But he seemed a throwback to the old fiscally conservative and socially moderate tradition of New England Republicans, a breed now all but extinct in the GOP. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/meet-steve-laffey-longest-long-shot-candidates/story?id=101554970">According</a> to ABC News, Laffey has almost no money and subatomic poll numbers—he has not yet placed on a national poll—and so he will be unlikely to qualify for the GOP debates. That&#39;s too bad, because <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.stevelaffey.com/about.html">one of his slogans</a> is: “​I did it for Cranston, I will do it for America,” which is kind of charming, and I would have loved to see Donald Trump even try to counter that by insulting the good people and city of Cranston.<br><br> —  Tom<br><br> <i>Katherine Hu contributed to this newsletter.</i><br><br> <em>When you buy a book using a link in this newsletter, we receive a commission. Thank you for supporting</em> The Atlantic <em>.</em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 22:11:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/mike-pence-trump-comments-2024-election/674948/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/08/mike-pence-trump-comments-2024-election/674948/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The AI Crackdown Is Coming]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Five ways for Washington to hold Silicon Valley accountable <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/dBFF1JdpsH_TvxHXzKP5LiSs5qc=/0x0:960x1200/648x810/media/img/2023/08/07/ai_2-2/original.gif" alt="柱的数字线框" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Joanne Imperio / The Atlantic</figcaption></figure> In April, lawyers for the airline Avianca noticed something strange. A passenger, Robert Mata, had sued the airline, alleging that a serving cart on a flight had struck and severely injured his left knee, but several cases cited in Mata&#39;s lawsuit <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/63107798/31/mata-v-avianca-inc/">didn&#39;t appear to exist</a> . The judge couldn&#39;t verify them, either. It turned out that ChatGPT had made them all up, fabricating names and decisions. One of Mata&#39;s lawyers, Steven A. Schwartz, had used the chatbot as an assistant—his first time using the program for legal research—and, as Schwartz <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/63107798/32/1/mata-v-avianca-inc/">wrote</a> in an affidavit, “was unaware of the possibility that its content could be false.”<br><br> The <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/05/27/nyregion/avianca-airline-lawsuit-chatgpt.html">incident</a> was only one in a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/03/business/media/ai-defamation-lies-accuracy.html">litany</a> of instances of generative AI spreading <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/6/9/23755057/openai-chatgpt-false-information-defamation-lawsuit">falsehoods</a> , not to mention <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/04/ai-voice-cloning-imposter-scams/673879/">financial scams</a> , nonconsensual <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/deepfake-porn-ai-misinformation/674475/">porn</a> , and more. Tech companies are marketing their AI products and potentially reaping enormous profits, with little accountability or legal oversight for the real-world damage those products can cause. The federal government is now trying to catch up.<br><br> Late last month, the Biden administration announced that seven tech companies at the forefront of AI development had agreed to a set of voluntary <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Ensuring-Safe-Secure-and-Trustworthy-AI.pdf">commitments</a> to ensure that their products are “safe, secure, and trustworthy.” Those commitments follow a flurry of White House <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/07/13/readout-of-vice-president-harriss-meeting-with-consumer-protection-labor-and-civil-rights-leaders-on-ai/">summits</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/05/04/readout-of-white-house-meeting-with-ceos-on-advancing-responsible-artificial-intelligence-innovation/">on AI</a> , <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/committee-activity/hearings/oversight-of-ai-rules-for-artificial-intelligence">congressional</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://science.house.gov/2023/6/artificial-intelligence-advancing-innovation-towards-the-national-interest">testimonies</a> on regulating the technology, and declarations from various government agencies that they are <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ftc.gov/policy/advocacy-research/tech-at-ftc/2023/06/generative-ai-raises-competition-concerns">taking</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nist.gov/itl/ai-risk-management-framework">AI</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/about-us/newsroom/cfpb-federal-partners-confirm-automated-systems-advanced-technology-not-an-excuse-for-lawbreaking-behavior/">seriously</a> . In the announcement, OpenAI, Microsoft, Google, Meta, and others pledged to subject their products to third-party testing, invest in bias reduction, and be more transparent about their AI systems&#39; capabilities and limitations.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-chatbot-human-evaluator-feedback/674805/">Read: America already has an AI underclass</a><br><br> The language is promising but also just a promise, lacking enforcement mechanisms and details about next steps. Regulating AI requires a lumbering bureaucracy to take on notoriously secretive companies and rapidly evolving technologies. Much of the Biden administration&#39;s language apes tech luminaries&#39; <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/ai-regulation-sam-altman-bill-gates/674278/">PR</a> lines about their products&#39; world-ending capacities, such as bioweapons and machines that “self-replicate.” Government action will be essential for safeguarding people&#39;s lives and livelihoods—not just from the supposed long-term threat of evil, superintelligent machines, but also from everyday threats. Generative AI has already exhibited gross biases and potential for misuse. And for more than a decade, less advanced but similarly opaque and often discriminatory algorithms have been used to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reuters.com/article/us-amazon-com-jobs-automation-insight-idUSKCN1MK08G">screen résumés</a> and determine <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.brookings.edu/articles/reducing-bias-in-ai-based-financial-services/">credit scores</a> , in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/society/2021/nov/09/ai-skin-cancer-diagnoses-risk-being-less-accurate-for-dark-skin-study">diagnostic software</a> , and as part of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/police-facial-recognition-technology-cant-tell-black-people-apart/">facial-recognition tools</a> .<br><br> I spoke with a number of experts and walked away with a list of five of the most effective ways the government could regulate AI to protect the country against the tech&#39;s quotidian risks, as well as its more hypothetical, apocalyptic dangers.<br><br> <strong>1. Don&#39;t take AI companies&#39; word on anything.</strong><br><br> A drug advertised for chemotherapy has to demonstrably benefit cancer patients in clinical trials, such as by shrinking tumors, and then get FDA approval. Then its manufacturer has to disclose side effects patients might experience. But no such accountability exists for AI products. “Companies are making claims about AI being able to do X or Y thing, but then not substantiating that they can,” Sarah Myers West, the managing director of the AI Now Institute and a former senior FTC adviser on AI, told me. Numerous tech firms have been criticized for <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.fastcompany.com/90597594/ai-algorithm-auditing-hirevue">misrepresenting</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.propublica.org/article/machine-bias-risk-assessments-in-criminal-sentencing">how</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.vice.com/en/article/qjpkmx/fac-recognition-company-lied-to-school-district-about-its-racist-tech">biased</a> or <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jwatch.org/na53777/2021/09/07/epics-sepsis-model-not-ready-prime-time">effective</a> their <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.brookings.edu/articles/a-guide-to-healthy-skepticism-of-artificial-intelligence-and-coronavirus/">algorithms</a> are, or providing almost <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3324874">no evidence</a> with which to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://predictive-optimization.cs.princeton.edu/">evaluate</a> them.<br><br> Mandating that AI tools undergo third-party testing to ensure that they meet agreed-upon metrics of bias, accuracy, and interpretability “is a really important first step,” Alexandra Givens, the president of the Center for Democracy and Technology, a nonprofit that advocates for privacy and human rights on the internet and receives some funding from the tech industry, told me. Companies could be compelled to disclose information about how their programs were trained, the software&#39;s limitations, and how they mitigated potential harms. “Right now, there&#39;s extraordinary information asymmetry,” she said—tech companies tend to reveal very little about how they train and validate their software. An audit could involve testing how often, say, a computer-vision program misrecognizes Black versus white faces or whether chatbots associate certain jobs with stereotypical gender roles (ChatGPT <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.aisnakeoil.com/p/quantifying-chatgpts-gender-bias">once</a> stated that attorneys cannot be pregnant, because attorneys must be men).<br><br> All of the experts I spoke with agreed that the tech companies themselves shouldn&#39;t be able to declare their own products safe. Otherwise, there is a substantial risk of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4227350">“audit washing”</a> —in which a dangerous product gains legitimacy from a meaningless stamp of approval, Ellen Goodman, a law professor at Rutgers, told me. Although numerous proposals currently call for <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.congress.gov/bill/117th-congress/house-bill/6580/text">after-the-fact</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/2023/07/06/new-york-ai-hiring-law">audits</a> , others have called for safety assessments to start much earlier. The potentially high-stakes applications of AI mean that these companies should “have to prove their products are not harmful before they can release them into the marketplace,” Safiya Noble, an internet-studies scholar at UCLA, told me.<br><br> Clear benchmarks and licenses are also crucial: A government standard would not be effective if watered down, and a hodgepodge of safety labels would breed confusion to the point of being illegible, similar to the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.eater.com/2019/7/17/20696498/whats-the-difference-cage-free-free-range-pasture-raised-eggs">differences</a> among free-range, cage-free, and pasture-raised eggs.<br><br> <strong>2. We don&#39;t need a Department of AI.</strong><br><br> Establishing basic assessments of and disclosures about AI systems wouldn&#39;t require a new government agency, even though that&#39;s what some tech executives <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsofts-president-backs-new-agency-to-regulate-chatgpt-other-ai-systems-c847bae0">have</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://techpolicy.press/transcript-senate-judiciary-subcommittee-hearing-on-oversight-of-ai/">called for</a> . Existing laws apply to many uses for AI: therapy bots, automated financial assistants, search engines promising truthful responses. In turn, the relevant federal agencies have the subject expertise to enforce those laws; for instance, the FDA could have to assess and approve a therapy bot like a medical device. “In naming a central AI agency that&#39;s going to do all the things, you lose the most important aspect of algorithmic assessment,” Givens said, “which is, what is the context in which it is being deployed, and what is the impact on that particular set of communities?”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/ai-regulation-sam-altman-bill-gates/674278/">Read: AI doomerism is a decoy</a><br><br> A new AI department could run the risk of creating <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/ai-regulation-sam-altman-bill-gates/674278/">regulatory capture</a> , with major AI companies staffing, advising, and lobbying the agency. Instead, experts told me, they&#39;d like to see more funding for existing agencies to hire staff and develop expertise on AI, which might require action from Congress. “There could be a very aggressive way in which existing enforcement agencies could be more empowered to do this if you provided them more resources,” Alex Hanna, the director of research at the Distributed AI Research Institute, told me.<br><br> <strong>3. The White House can lead by example.</strong><br><br> Far-reaching legislation to regulate AI could take years and face challenges from tech companies in court. Another, possibly faster approach could involve the federal government acting by example in the AI models it uses, the research it supports, and the funding it disburses. For instance, earlier this year, a federal task force <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/ostp/news-updates/2023/01/24/national-artificial-intelligence-research-resource-task-force-releases-final-report/">recommended</a> that the government commit $2.6 billion to funding AI research and development. Any company hoping to access those resources could be forced to meet a number of standards, which could lead to industry-wide adoption—somewhat akin to the tax incentives and subsidies <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2022/10/inflation-reduction-act-climate-economy/671659/">encouraging</a> green energy in the Inflation Reduction Act.<br><br> The government is also a major <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.brookings.edu/articles/understanding-artificial-intelligence-spending-by-the-u-s-federal-government/">purchaser</a> and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.com/news/2023/07/19/gary-peters-ai-laws-washington-00106922">user</a> of AI itself, and could require its vendors to subject themselves to audits and release transparency reports. “The biggest thing the Biden administration can do is make it binding administration policy that AI can only be purchased, developed, used if it goes through meaningful testing for safety, efficacy, nondiscrimination, and protecting people&#39;s privacy,” Givens told me.<br><br> <strong>4. AI needs a tamper-proof seal.</strong><br><br> Deepfakes and other synthetic media—images, videos, and audio clips that an AI system can whip up in seconds—have already spread <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/03/generative-ai-disinformation-synthetic-media-history/673260/">misinformation</a> and been used in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/deepfake-porn-ai-misinformation/674475/">nonconsensual pornography</a> . Last month&#39;s voluntary commitments include developing a watermark to tell users they are interacting with AI-generated content, but the language is vague and the path forward unclear. Many existing methods of watermarking, such as the block of rainbow pixels at the bottom of any image generated by <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://openai.com/dall-e-2">DALL-E 2</a> , are easy to manipulate or <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://help.openai.com/en/articles/6468065-dall-e-content-policy-faq">remove</a> . A more robust method would involve logging where, when, and how a piece of media was created—like a digital stamp from a camera—as well as every edit it undergoes. Companies including Adobe, Microsoft, and Sony are already working to implement one such <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://c2pa.org/">standard</a> , although such approaches might be difficult for the public to understand.<br><br> Sam Gregory, the executive director of the human-rights organization Witness, told me that government standards for labeling AI-generated content would need to be enforced throughout the AI supply chain by everybody from the makers of text-to-image models to app and web-browser developers. We need a tamper-proof seal, not a sticker.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2022/12/deepfake-synthetic-media-technology-rise-disinformation/672519/">Read: It&#39;s time to worry about deepfakes again</a><br><br> To encourage the adoption of a standard way to denote AI content, Goodman told me, the government could mandate that web browsers, computers, and other devices recognize the label. Such a mandate would be similar to the federal <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.fcc.gov/consumers/guides/v-chip-putting-restrictions-what-your-children-watch">requirement</a> that new televisions include a part, known as a “V-chip,” that recognizes the maturity ratings set by the TV industry, which parents can use to block programs.<br><br> <strong>5. Build ways for people to protect their work from AI.</strong><br><br> Multiple high-profile lawsuits are currently accusing AI models, such as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/7/9/23788741/sarah-silverman-openai-meta-chatgpt-llama-copyright-infringement-chatbots-artificial-intelligence-ai">ChatGPT</a> and the image-generator <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.artnews.com/art-in-america/features/midjourney-ai-art-image-generators-lawsuit-1234665579/">Midjourney</a> , of stealing writers&#39; and artists&#39; work. Intellectual property has become central to debates over generative AI, and two general types of copyright infringement are at play: the images, text, and other data the models are trained on, and the images and text they spit back out.<br><br> On the input side, allegations that generative-AI models are violating copyright law may stumble in court, Daniel Gervais, a law professor at Vanderbilt, told me. Making copies of images, articles, videos, and other media online to develop a training dataset likely falls under “fair use,” because training an AI model on the material meaningfully transforms it. The standard for proving copyright violations on the output side may also pose difficulties, because proving that an AI output is similar to a specific copyrighted work—not just in the style of Kehinde Wiley, but the spitting image of one of his paintings—is a high legal threshold.<br><br> Gervais said he imagines that a market-negotiated agreement between rights-holders and AI developers will arrive before any sort of legal standard. In the EU, for instance, artists and writers can <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://creativecommons.org/2023/06/14/european-parliament-gives-green-light-to-ai-act-moving-eu-towards-finalizing-the-worlds-leading-regulation-of-ai/">opt out</a> of having their work used to train AI, which could incentivize a deal that&#39;s in the interest of both artists and Silicon Valley. “Publishers see this as a source of income, and the tech companies have invested so much in their technology,” Gervais said. Another possible option would be an even more stringent <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ipwatchdog.com/2023/07/13/senate-ip-subcommittee-mulls-federal-right-publicity-ai-copyright-hearing/id=163469/">opt-in standard</a> , which would require anybody owning copyrighted material to provide explicit permission for their data to be used. In the US, Gervais said, an option to opt out may be unnecessary. A <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.copyright.gov/legislation/dmca.pdf">law</a> passed to protect copyright on the internet makes it <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/17/1202">illegal</a> to strip a file of its “copyright management information,” such as labels with the work&#39;s creator and date of publication, and many observers <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://stablediffusionlitigation.com/pdf/00201/1-1-stable-diffusion-complaint.pdf">allege</a> that creating datasets to train generative AI violates that law. The fine for removing such information could run up to <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.copyright.gov/title17/92chap12.html">tens of thousands of dollars per work</a> , and even higher for other copyright infringements—a financial risk that, multiplied by perhaps millions of violations in a dataset, could be too big for companies to take.<br><br> Few, if any, of these policies are guaranteed. They face numerous practical, political, and legal hurdles, not least of which is Silicon Valley&#39;s formidable <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2023-07-05/ai-congress-regulation-lobbying">lobbying arm</a> . Nor will such regulations alone be enough to stop all the ways the tech can negatively affect Americans. AI is rife with the privacy violations, monopolistic business practices, and poor treatment of workers, all of which have plagued the tech industry for years.<br><br><br> But <em>some</em> sort of regulation is coming: The Biden administration has said it is working on <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/07/21/fact-sheet-biden-harris-administration-secures-voluntary-commitments-from-leading-artificial-intelligence-companies-to-manage-the-risks-posed-by-ai/#:~:text=The%20Biden%2DHarris%20Administration%20is%20currently%20developing%20an%20executive%20order,the%20way%20in%20responsible%20innovation.&amp;text=The%20companies%20commit%20to%20internal,AI%20systems%20before%20their%20release.">bipartisan legislation</a> , and it promised guidance on the responsible use of AI by federal agencies before <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/05/04/fact-sheet-biden-harris-administration-announces-new-actions-to-promote-responsible-ai-innovation-that-protects-americans-rights-and-safety/">the end of summer</a> ; <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.google.com/search?q=ai+lead+act&amp;rlz=1C5GCEM_enUS1015US1023&amp;oq=ai+lead+act&amp;aqs=chrome.0.0i512l2j0i22i30j0i390i650l2j69i60l3.969j0j4&amp;sourceid=chrome&amp;ie=UTF-8">numerous</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.congress.gov/bill/118th-congress/senate-bill/1356">bills</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hawley.senate.gov/sites/default/files/2023-06/Hawley-No-Section-230-Immunity-for-AI-Act.pdf">are</a> pending before Congress. Until then, tech companies may just continue to roll out new and untested products, no matter who or what is steamrolled in the process.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 21:23:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/ai-misinformation-scams-government-regulation/674946/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/ai-misinformation-scams-government-regulation/674946/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Trump Is Acting Like He’s Cornered]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The former president&#39;s response to the latest indictment <span>suggests a man rattled in a way he seldom has been before.</span> <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/rn9qeKhbA3Ed8QcVbC6TwdHXfyQ=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/trump-1/original.jpg" alt="唐纳德·特朗普，从后面看" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Christopher Aluka Berry / Reuters</figcaption></figure> In some ways, Donald Trump&#39;s mental state is more transparent than nearly any public figure&#39;s: He has no shame, little discretion, and ample channels to broadcast his feelings in real time. Yet his constant stream of consciousness and always elevated dudgeon make it hard to parse the finer fluctuations in his mood.<br><br> Even so, the former president&#39;s public behavior since Special Counsel Jack Smith <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trump-indicted-january-6-jack-smith/674886/">indicted him last week</a> suggests a man feeling cornered. This isn&#39;t to say that Trump <em>is</em> cornered—his ability to escape tough situations makes him the envy of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newsweek.com/cats-nine-lives-myth-explained-1643381">every house cat</a> —but his handling of the case suggests a man rattled in a way he seldom has been before.<br><br> The former president has attacked Smith in terms that are strikingly personal, even for him. He has also attacked Tanya Chutkan, the federal judge assigned to hear the case. He delivered angry speeches in Alabama and South Carolina. He jeered the US Women&#39;s National Team, blamed President Joe Biden for its early exit from the World Cup, and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/110842705795010789">unintelligibly ridiculed</a> former House Speaker Nancy Pelosi (“She is a Wicked Witch whose husbands journey from hell starts and finishes with her. She is a sick &amp; demented psycho who will someday live in HELL!”). He sent his attorney out to do all five major Sunday-morning TV programs. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.thedailybeast.com/theres-a-good-reason-trump-aides-dont-think-the-new-indictment-is-a-joke?ref=home?ref=home?ref=home"><em>The Daily Beast</em> spoke</a> with Trump insiders who reported serious apprehensions inside his camp.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/trump-indicted-january-6-jack-smith/674886/">David A. Graham: Trump attempted a brazen, dead-serious attack on American democracy</a><br><br> But what neither he nor his allies have done is offer a coherent account of his actions—one that would suggest that he didn&#39;t conspire to overthrow the duly elected government. This is likely for the simple reason that he conspired to overthrow the duly elected government.<br><br> “Deranged Jack Smith is going before his number one draft pick, the Judge of his &#39;dreams&#39; (WHO MUST BE RECUSED!), in an attempt to take away my FIRST AMENDMENT RIGHTS - This, despite the fact that he, the DOJ, and his many Thug prosecutors, are illegally leaking, everything and anything, to the Fake News Media!!!” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/110848362917019858">Trump wrote</a> on his Truth Social site this morning.<br><br> This message followed a string of other rants in recent days, including attacks on former Vice President Mike Pence (“Liddle&#39; Mike Pence, a man who was about to be ousted as Governor Indiana until I came along and made him VP, has gone to the Dark Side”) and Chutkan (“THERE IS NO WAY I CAN GET A FAIR TRIAL WITH THE JUDGE “ASSIGNED” TO THE RIDICULOUS FREEDOM OF SPEECH/FAIR ELECTIONS CASE”).<br><br> Attacking the judge and the prosecutor in your case is not generally recommended as a defense strategy, but then, Trump has little use for courtesy, niceties, or basic common sense. Smith is clearly paying attention; prosecutors cited an ambiguously threatening social-media post in a court filing just hours after it was posted. (“IF YOU GO AFTER ME, I&#39;M COMING AFTER YOU!&quot; the message said; a Trump spokesperson claimed that this was actually directed at “the RINO, China-loving, dishonest special interest groups and Super PACs.”) The difference between Trump&#39;s broadsides against Chutkan, a Black Obama appointee who hasn&#39;t even had a chance to make any consequential decisions in the case yet, and his lack of criticism for Judge Aileen Cannon, the Trump appointee overseeing the Florida case over his mishandling of classified documents, is notable if not surprising.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trump-indictment-gop-jan-6/674895/">Ronald Brownstein: Trump&#39;s threat to democracy is now systemic</a><br><br> Discerning Trump&#39;s agitation is easy enough; determining the goal of his outbursts is not so straightforward. One interpretation is that he&#39;s trying to goad Smith&#39;s team and turn its members from prosecutors into persecutors, baiting them to overreact or demand onerous conditions, which Trump could in turn use to demand a venue change or appeal a conviction. But this is reminiscent of the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://knowyourmeme.com/memes/profit"><em>South Park</em> –birthed underpants-gnome meme</a> : The first steps and desired outcome are clear, but it&#39;s completely mysterious what the middle steps might be. For all Trump&#39;s comments that Smith is “deranged,” the special counsel instead seems preternaturally, even uncannily, impassive. Chutkan, like other DC judges, has rejected prior claims that January 6 trials can&#39;t be fairly held in the district.<br><br> An alternative theory is that Trump is just playing to the court of public opinion rather than the court of law. Yesterday, Trump&#39;s attorney John Lauro did the circuit of Sunday shows, a maneuver that Beltway nerds call the “Full Ginsburg,” after William Ginsburg, an attorney for Monica Lewinsky who pioneered it to respond to reports about his client&#39;s relationship with then-President Bill Clinton. It&#39;s a powerful public-relations tool— <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Full_Ginsburg">used by candidates for president</a> , for example—but somewhat baffling as a pretrial maneuver.<br><br> Trump is often more interested in rousing his supporters than pursuing a prudent defense, apparently concluding that whatever his problems with the law, his political clout will be enough to evade or at least finesse the jeopardy. In the two federal cases against him, he may finally be facing charges that are not so easily circumvented, but his response has not necessarily caught up.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/jeffrey-clark-doj-weaponization-trump-indictment/674898/">David A. Graham: The real weaponization of the Justice Department</a><br><br> On some level, the PR offensive might be working. More than half of Americans, according to a new <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/trump-indictment-jan-6-opinion-poll-2023-08-06/">CBS News/YouGov poll</a> , think the charges against Trump are aimed at hurting his 2024 campaign, though solid majorities also think the charges are about upholding rule of law and defending democracy. But the actual arguments Lauro offered on TV don&#39;t seem especially well crafted, and seem likely instead to reinforce the reality that whether the public wants him convicted or not, it is appalled by Trump&#39;s attempt at stealing the election.<br><br> Lauro argued in different appearances that Trump&#39;s alleged behavior was “aspirational.” For example, “What President Trump didn&#39;t do is direct Vice President Pence to do anything,” Lauro said on CNN. “He asked him in an aspirational way.” He also called Trump&#39;s request for Georgia Secretary of State Brad Raffensperger to “find 11,780 votes” an “aspirational ask.” This is the kind of distinction without a difference that gives legalism a bad name. Lauro also said that even if Trump committed a “technical violation of the Constitution,” he didn&#39;t commit a crime. But telling the public that your client violated the Constitution seems like a questionable PR decision.<br><br> Neither Lauro, in his five appearances, nor Trump, going back to his initial response to the indictment, has actually rebutted the charges. Trump has claimed that the government is attacking his right to free speech, but he has made nearly no effort to question the specifics of the charges. A rare example is his denial of Pence&#39;s claim that Trump said he was “too honest.” More broadly, Trump hasn&#39;t offered any bigger explanation for his weeks-long push to subvert the election. If Trump is acting as though he&#39;s cornered, that is because he doesn&#39;t have a good answer to this question.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 19:37:08 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trumps-unhinged-attacks-smith-and-chutkan/674945/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/donald-trumps-unhinged-attacks-smith-and-chutkan/674945/ </item><item><title><![CDATA['Working Class' Does Not Equal 'White']]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>布莱尔·LM·凯利在她的新书中探讨了一段被忽视的历史：奴隶制以来作为一名黑人工人意味着什么。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/g5hsMAOPoqhS1Gpy07bnbWnA6Wc=/1x92:3575x4560/648x810/media/img/2023/08/04/GettyImages_534998784/original.jpg" alt="拿着金属杆的工人" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>杰里·库克/Corbis/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>在许多美国人心目中<i>，工人阶级</i>这个词与<i>白人工人阶级</i>是同义词，这是一个政治神话的结果。正如屡获殊荣的历史学家布莱尔·LM·凯利（Blair LM Kelley）在她的新书<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/black-folk-the-roots-of-the-black-working-class-blair-lm-kelley/9781631496554?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《黑人：黑人工人阶级的根源》</i></a>中所解释的那样，黑人比白人更有可能成为工人阶级。<br><br>凯利的<i>《黑人民间》</i>向黑人工人敞开了心扉，讲述了他们在 200 多年的美国历史中复杂的生活。凯利回顾了她自己的工人阶级祖先的历史，以及构成黑人劳工世界的洗衣女工、普尔曼搬运工、家庭女佣和邮政工人的历史。他们的快乐。他们的技能。他们的挑战。她还为我们这个时代持续存在的关于黑人工人的种族主义思想提供了历史背景，同时强调了黑人劳工组织始终帮助反击偏见的方式。<br><br>关于种族和阶级的神话继续主导我们的政治话语。首先，根据定义，没有大学学位的美国人是“工人阶级”是一个神话。积累或继承的财富是比教育（或工资）更准确的阶级地位指标，特别是在美国<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.americanprogress.org/article/eliminating-black-white-wealth-gap-generational-challenge/">种族贫富差距</a>巨大的情况下。成员拥有大学学位的黑人家庭的财富水平<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.urban.org/urban-wire/why-do-black-college-graduates-have-lower-homeownership-rate-white-people-who-dropped-out-high-school">与成员没有高中文凭的白人家庭的财富水平相似</a>。这些白人高中辍学者的住房拥有率高于黑人大学毕业生。即使我们通过大学学历来衡量工人阶级的地位，美国白人 (50.2%) 也<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.kqed.org/mindshift/61037/college-completion-rates-are-up-for-all-americans-but-racial-gaps-persist">远远</a>高于美国黑人 (34.2%)、拉丁美洲人 (27.8%) 和美国原住民 (25.4%)拥有大学学位，因此通过这种不充分的衡量标准，不属于工人阶级。<br><br>正如凯利在<i>《黑人民间》</i>中指出的那样，“白人工人阶级是唐纳德·特朗普的支持者的代名词”也是一个神话。事实上， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2017/06/05/its-time-to-bust-the-myth-most-trump-voters-were-not-working-class/">特朗普的支持者仍然比普遍描述的富裕得多</a>。 “这不一定是[特朗普选民]需要接受教育的问题，”凯利在我们最近谈话时告诉我。 “这是人们对自己在世界上的地位做出的一系列选择，以及让他们感到被验证和认可的因素。”<br><br>所有这些神话构成了我们的“国家神话”，“为黑人工人留下了很少的空间”，即将上任的北卡罗来纳大学教堂山分校美国南方研究中心主任凯利写道。我们讨论了我们可以从他们的历史、日常生活和政治组织中汲取哪些教训。我们的谈话始于我们最了解的黑人：我们的家人。<br><br><i>为了清晰起见，本次采访经过精简和编辑。</i><br><br> <b>《伊布拉姆·X·肯迪：</b><i>黑人民间》</i>一书首先记录了你外祖父的生活故事，他在佐治亚州东北部的卡农镇面临并与种族主义作斗争。让我印象深刻的是，我的外祖父阿尔文来自盖顿，盖顿也位于佐治亚州东部，但距离萨凡纳更近。他也在那里处理种族主义问题，逃到了纽约市。你的外祖父前往北卡罗来纳州。这样的相似之处。你为什么决定从这里开始写这本书？<br><br> <b>Blair LM Kelley：</b>这对我的家人来说是一个影响深远的故事。这是我母亲重复了很多很多次的一句话。我想我的母亲真的希望我了解奴隶制已经结束的程度，但征服的情况却没有。她想让我明白这与我的生活经历有多接近，这并不是遥远的、早已消失的事情。<br><br>将我的家人与这段更宏大的历史联系起来，我知道这是很多人被迫逃离的故事。我真的很想从这个开始，因为我知道它有多么普遍。<br><br><b>肯迪：</b>你特别希望<i>《黑人民间》</i>能够“捕捉黑人工人的生活特征，不仅将他们视为劳动者、阶级成员或活动家，而且将他们视为日常经历很重要的人。”为什么捕捉他们一生的性格如此重要？<br><br><b>凯利：</b>我从来没有真正认为自己是一名劳工历史学家。劳工史非常关注机构和工会以及组织之间的内斗。这些很有趣，也是你需要知道的事情。但它们并不是我认识家人的方式。我的父母都是工人，但他们的生活，他们的整个生活，影响了他们对工作的看法。我还没有看到那么多关注整体存在的劳动史。这不仅仅是工厂车间版本的历史，而是一座教堂、一座房子、一种母女关系。我希望看到这些事情得到放大，因为我认为它们对员工的生活同样有意义，甚至比原子化工作空间更有意义。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1913/06/the-negro-and-the-labor-unions/529524/">阅读：布克·华盛顿在大西洋谈工会和公民权利</a><br><br><b>肯迪：</b>你首先写了一个出生于奴隶制的铁匠，然后转向其他工作，比如洗衣女工、火车车厢搬运工、家庭女佣和邮政工人。为什么特别是那些职业？今天黑人工人所从事的特定职业是否有我们可能视为原型或与其中一些历史工作相似的职业？<br><br><b>凯利：</b>我认为家政工人仍然是一个令人难以置信的群体。他们的组织真的令人难以置信，我想在未来的工作中继续思考这一点。我现在对跟踪邮政工作人员非常感兴趣。我认为，特别是在新冠疫情期间，我们可以看到围绕邮政工作展开的一场真正的斗争，我认为值得继续关注。这场大流行再次让我们想到了医疗保健中的黑人，特别是经过认证的护理助理。这些护士队伍中大部分是黑人女性，她们在疫情中首当其冲。零工经济对我来说也很有趣。黑人在这个领域的比例也过高。<br><br><b>肯迪：</b>你写道，当提到黑人工人时，工作的概念就完全被抛弃了。相反，他们被描述为“穷人”，并且常常暗示他们没有价值、没有生产力。这与被奴役的黑人懒惰和缺乏动力的特征相呼应。你在书的开头写下这一点是为了真正为更大的争论奠定基础。那个更大的论点是什么？<br><br><b>凯利：</b>我认为，在奴隶制中出生的黑人工人阶级周围存在着令人难以置信的错误逻辑。我引用了托马斯·杰斐逊（Thomas Jefferson）的话，他观察了黑人，并在<i>《弗吉尼亚州笔记》</i>中写道，他们睡得很多。我想，<i>先生，当你坐在椅子上，有人给你扇风，给你送食物，你说谁懒惰？</i>因此，我们当代思维中的刻板印象及其来世对我来说是一个令人困惑的问题。这是我真正想要面对、解开并贯穿全文的线索。因为黑人工人对这个国家的贡献是巨大的。因此，称黑人为“懒惰”或“穷人”误解了我们所做的事情以及我们如何看待自己。<br><br> <b>Kendi：</b>您还指出，存在一种误解，认为黑人工人缺乏技能。特别是在写关于洗衣女工的文章时，您写到了所需的巨大技能。这些黑人工人缺乏技能的想法是否与他们缺乏动力和懒惰的想法有关——这是这种想法的延伸？<br><br><b>凯利：</b>是的。我对学者们用来理解工作的熟练劳动力/非熟练劳动力动态着迷。疫情期间，给我的印象真的很深刻。农场工人联合组织正在播放农场工人捆绑萝卜、采摘花椰菜、收割芦笋的视频，他们的移动速度之快，你几乎看不到他们是如何做到的。他们被归类为非技术工人。直到今天，我们仍然会这样描述它们。因此，对我来说，阅读有关采摘棉花、洗衣服或在普尔曼汽车上工作的报道——所有这些事情都需要知识、学习和技能。我只是想推翻关于什么是熟练的、什么是非熟练的学术假设。<br><br><b>肯迪：</b>许多过去（甚至今天）被称为非技术人员的黑人从事与服务相关的职业。我提到这一点是因为存在种族主义观念，认为黑人本质上是奴性的，这削弱了黑人实际上在从事这些工作方面拥有高技能的观念。你也看到了吗？<br><br><b>凯利：</b>是的。我认为，当你看看像普尔曼搬运工这样的人时，他们中的许多人都受过高等教育——如果他们受过一些教育，他们就会受到优先考虑。因为能够进行对话，预测人们的需求——他们确实是火车车厢上礼宾服务的第一种形式——这确实需要大量的知识和技能，而这看起来只是一份工作。它提醒我们，许多人在我们认为是服务的事情上表现出了敏捷的思维。<br><br>他们互相服务的方式，并利用他们的平台为所有工人设想更好的权利，这真的令人难以置信。我们常常认为工会是自私的。这是我们对工会的负面叙述的一部分。他们向工人收取费用，但他们没有做太多事情，也没有真正提供帮助。但当我们看到像卧车搬运工兄弟会这样的工会时，我们看到他们开始在整个国家范围内扩展我们的公民和公民权利概念。<br><br> <b>Kendi：</b>事实上，卧车搬运工兄弟会的创始人 A. Phillip Randolph 是 1963 年华盛顿游行的幕后黑手，马丁·路德·金博士在这次游行中发表了“我有一个梦想”的演讲。这些汽车搬运工努力提升自己。但你写到，当黑人工人能够开始赚更多的钱，或拥有土地，甚至开办企业时，他们通常会避免“成功的外在迹象”。种族主义者认为他们傲慢，甚至忘记了自己的地位。但黑人精英呢？他们对当时和现在的黑人工人阶级有何看法？<br><br><b>凯利：</b>如果你回顾一下 19 世纪末和 20 世纪初的黑人报纸，你会发现他们告诫工人，“不要出去把钱花在这些特殊的事情上。要非常节俭。不要去酒吧买这些漂亮的衣服在周日穿。”因此，这与当前的黑人精英有相似之处。这是黑人社区长期以来一直流传的一个古老的比喻：以某种方式，你可以通过某种方式摆脱使工人阶级生活变得更加困难的环境。<br><br>享乐的空间、享受的空间以及对你的外表和拥有的东西感到自豪的空间，以及工薪阶层花钱的方式一直受到批评。 “我看起来不像我的工作；我看起来像我想要的样子”——这种自豪感传统上是黑人工人阶级的东西。虽然今天戴上Gucci腰带什么的看起来很不一样。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/04/how-build-union-victory-amazon-staten-island/629464/">阅读：有组织的劳工正在卷土重来吗？</a><br><br><b>肯迪：</b>黑人工人阶级成员不仅为快乐、享受和自豪开辟了空间。他们为政治、组织和工会开辟了空间。您谈到今天黑人工人阶级的成员比任何其他种族群体更有可能成为工会成员。根据您的研究，您认为为什么会发生这种情况？也就是说，你认为为什么黑人处于我们这个时代工会组织和激进主义热潮的最前沿？<br><br><b>凯利：</b>我认为黑人工人对工会的叙述以及工会可能具有的价值有不同的看法。黑人工人已经采取了批判的立场，他们说：“好吧，不，让我自己评估一下。不，实际上我认为工会会有帮助！”走到一起是帮助我们、提升我们的一种方式。它符合我们在家庭和社区中所生活的更广泛生活的叙述。工会只是与黑人社区随着时间的推移而奋斗的方式产生共鸣，这就是为什么我们看到黑人从自由的最初时刻一直到现在都在组建工会。<br><br><b>肯迪：</b>你甚至将被奴役的黑人逃跑描述为参与新生的劳工罢工。<br><br><b>凯利：</b>当然。他们明白自己的劳动带来了多大的改变。我们常常忘记，被征服的人也有理智的生活。<br><br><b>肯迪：</b>当然。这让我想起了你书中的两句话，我希望你能反思一下。第一部分涉及我们刚才谈论的内容——米妮·萨维奇（Minnie Savage），一个受剥削和受限制的佃农的孩子，如何知道她在弗吉尼亚州阿科马克县采摘庄稼的价值。 16岁时，她逃亡。你写道：“米妮梦想生活在一个不再感觉自己是奴隶的地方。一个她的辛勤工作可以得到公平报酬的地方。一个她可以安全地与其他人一起要求公平待遇的地方。她不得不离开阿科马克才能“摆脱自由”。<br><br><b>凯利：</b>我喜欢米妮这个人物，能接受她的采访真是一份礼物。她恰好来自我祖父的家乡。当她前往费城时，跟随她真是太有趣了。请记住，对于很多人来说，移民是一个充满可能性的伟大梦想，是一种新的、更广泛的、更强大的事物的愿景。记录了她对移民后头几十年所发生的事情的失望，然后也记录了她最终确实得到了更强大的东西，以及她真正感到自豪的东西——她是一个令人惊叹的人物。<br><br><b>肯迪：</b>最后：“特朗普引发的对白人工人阶级的痴迷……掩盖了这样一个现实：美国最活跃、最投入、最有见识和最热情的工人阶级是黑人工人阶级。”<br><br><b>凯利：</b>我是一位研究黑人的学者，我爱黑人。我认为，当我们转移目光，当我们以不同的方式思考，当我们关注他人并从他们的历史中收集信息时，我们会学到很多东西。黑人生活可以教会我们很多东西，让我们知道什么是可能的。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 14:28:23 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/08/black-folk-book-working-class-blair-lm-kelley/674935/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/08/black-folk-book-working-class-blair-lm-kelley/674935/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Seven Books That Will Make You Put Down Your Phone]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这些标题有意识地旨在吸引读者的注意力。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/caY-Vi1xSW7IkSFO8j6GwbHQ9rA=/0x0:3500x1969/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/Atlantic_1/original.jpg" alt="一本封面上有很多眼球的书，每个人看起来都不同" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>马特·蔡斯的插图</figcaption></figure>当我给本科生教授文学课时，我最重要的任务之一就是帮助我的学生重新学习如何在分心的时代阅读。我给他们布置了一个练习：设定 20 分钟的计时器，然后埋头读书，看不到手机，并且在闹钟响之前不要停下来。他们经常告诉我，当他们这样做时，时间的流逝会有所不同。最初的几分钟很拖沓，而且练习感觉完全不可能且无聊，但当他们继续坐着阅读时，他们开始关注面前书页内的世界。到最后，他们通常会对计时器的响起感到惊讶，并渴望继续阅读。<br><br>我的学生并不是唯一从这项练习中受益的人，而且这项活动适用于任何书籍。但这份清单将为您提供一个良好的开端。下面的七个标题有意识地旨在吸引读者的注意力，无论是通过形式还是内容。每一篇都会以不同的方式引导您阅读：有些简短而简洁；有些则简洁明了。其他的则又长又蔓延。有些使用第二人称直接向读者讲话；有些则使用第二人称。其他人则深入研究某一主题并邀请您一起参与。但它们的共同点是都能刷新你的观察力，让你最终以一种新的方式看待现实世界。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/mrs-caliban-rachel-ingalls/9780811226691?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>《卡利班夫人》</em></strong></a> <strong>，雷切尔·英格尔斯著</strong><br><br>我向陷入阅读低谷的人推荐的第一本书是<em>《卡利班夫人》</em> ，这是一本不到 150 页的中篇小说，情节引人入胜，节奏很快。 <em>《卡利班夫人》</em>写于 1982 年，但于 2017 年重新发行，讲述了 20 世纪 50 年代风格的孤独家庭主妇多萝西遇见拉里的故事，拉里是一种两栖海洋生物，看起来几乎与人类一模一样，只是皮肤呈绿色，手脚有蹼。拉里在多萝西的家里躲避了科学家的绑架，两人在她丈夫弗雷德的眼皮底下发生了一段奇怪的恋情。多萝西和弗雷德“太不高兴了，不愿意离婚”，所以拉里实际上是一位受欢迎的客人，他不仅为多萝西提供有关水下世界的异国故事，而且还倾听她作为家庭主妇的挣扎。人们（包括我的学生）推测吉列尔莫·德尔·托罗的电影<em>《水形物语》</em>大致是根据《<em>卡利班夫人》</em>改编的，这是有道理的——英格尔斯的写作具有催眠性和电影感，而<em>《卡利班夫人》</em>是那种你可以一口气读完的书。坐着：它像大片一样吸引你的注意力。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1986/04/discovery-of-the-month/667376/">阅读：本月发现（自 1986 年起）</a><br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-fifth-season-n-k-jemisin/9780316229296?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>第五季</em></strong></a><strong>，作者 NK Jemisin</strong><br><br><em>第五季</em>的结尾有我在任何推理小说或奇幻小说中最喜欢的部分：在情节停止后出现的大量术语表，例如<em>食石者</em>、<em>无社群</em>和<em>原原者</em>，帮助读者解释极其非传统的事物。书的世界。这在这里很有帮助，因为这个复杂的故事发生在一个名为“寂静”的超级大陆上，该大陆正处于其常规启示录的边缘，即所谓的“第五季”，即灾难性气候变化的时期。能够利用热能制造地震事件的“原原人”被认为是危险的人，大多数人都躲藏起来，远离社会。杰米辛的主角埃松就是其中之一，她隐藏自己的真实身份，在村庄里担任教师。有一天，她回到家，发现她的丈夫谋杀了她的儿子并绑架了她的女儿——她们都继承了她的力量。当她周围的世界崩溃时，她必须在一个神秘的孩子的陪伴下踏上拯救女儿的旅程。读完<em>第五季</em>的几章后，您将沉浸在这个新世界及其错综复杂的世界中，并为这个社会结构揭示我们自己最糟糕的现实的方式而着迷。<br><br><strong>伊塔洛·卡尔维诺《</strong> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/if-on-a-winter-s-night-a-traveler-italo-calvino/9780156439619?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>如果是冬夜的旅人》</em></strong></a><br><br>一个具有实验性或神秘结构的故事会让你变成一名侦探，不仅试图弄清楚发生了什么，而且还试图弄清楚为什么写作是这样的。对我来说，这方面最令人愉快的作品是伊塔洛·卡尔维诺（Italo Calvino）的<em>《如果冬夜的旅行者》</em> ，这本书讲述了一个被称为“读者”并被称为“你”的人的故事，他在尝试阅读一本名为<em>《如果》</em>的小说时不断受到削弱。伊塔洛·卡尔维诺的<em>《冬夜的旅行者》</em> 。读者立刻发现他的副本印刷错误，与另一本小说装订在一起，然后他购买了这本小说——但他只进入了第二个选择，然后第二个选择也被打断了。他拿起的每本小说都被没收、未完成、丢失或充满错误。但当读者一个接一个地阅读故事，却永远无法读完时，他遇到了他的女性对手卢德米拉，她正在尝试阅读相同的标题。他们不可能的旅程的循环是后现代的，但基调并不抽象或理智——它有趣而甜蜜。卡尔维诺小说的元小说，字面上是写给“你”的，戏剧化地表现了集中注意力和找到合适的书的困难。具有讽刺意味的是，这本书非常容易阅读，因为读者的选择从浪漫小说到惊悚小说再到现实主义小说，所有这些都与一个男人寻找爱情的旅程交织在一起。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/her-body-and-other-parties-stories-carmen-maria-machado/9781555977887?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>《她的身体和其他派对》</em></strong></a> <strong>，卡门·玛丽亚·马查多 (Carmen Maria Machado) 着</strong><br><br>短篇小说集可以采用大多数小说所不能的多种基调和风格——每个故事都可以是完全独特的。 <em>《她的身体和其他派对》的内容</em>范围令人难以置信，其中包含了有趣的、奇异的、不真实的和令人难以忘怀的内容，任何读者都能在其中找到一些吸引人的东西。马查多在中篇小说《特别令人发指》的旁边重新构思了脖子上系着绿丝带的女孩的故事，其中<em>《法律与秩序：特殊受害者》中</em>的角色与鬼魂和分身展开斗争。即使当她重复观众熟悉的电视节目时，马查多也会让已知的世界看起来很陌生；结果，超自然现象开始显得越来越合乎逻辑。在另一个故事《盘点》中，一名妇女列出了她所有的性经历，而世界正慢慢被流行病吞噬。她对过去事物的怀旧变成了对世界现状的恐惧——她的清单表面上回忆过去，但实际上讲述现在，成为应对每天带来的不确定性的一种方式。同样， <em>《她的身体和其他派对》</em>中的每个故事都同时做了很多事情，每种类型都有倾向，每个第一印象都不可靠，总是新鲜但也令人恐惧。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/gathering-moss-a-natural-and-cultural-history-of-mosses-robin-wall-kimmerer/9780870714993?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>收集苔藓</em></strong></a><strong>，罗宾·沃尔·基默勒 (Robin Wall Kimmerer)</strong><br><br>基默勒的第一本书<em>《采集苔藓》</em>中，关注不是主题，而是模式。尽管她 2013 年的作品<em>《Braiding Sweetgrass》</em>深入探讨了土著知识体系和科学知识体系之间的许多重叠之处，但 Kimmerer 在这里只专注于一种生物：苔藓。在一系列简短的个人文章中，她审视了苔藓的微小世界以及它能教给我们什么。她认为，莫斯可以为我们的生活提供隐喻，帮助我们理解我们的人际关系，并向我们展示微小的事物如何秩序更大的世界。凭借她作为科学家和土著学者的背景，她向我们展示了这个微小的世界是多么丰富、多么值得尊重，以及多么令人震惊的美丽。基默勒写道，在检查苔藓后，她从显微镜中抬起头来，“对平凡世界的朴素、单调和可预测的形状感到惊讶”。基默勒的个人风格注入了多样性：每篇文章不仅提供了有关她正在观察的生物体的新信息，还提供了有关她在房屋、实验室和社区中的许多角色的新信息。最后，她启发读者像她一样看待，密切关注生活中最小的部分。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/01/black-writers-environmental-literature-exclusion/672835/">阅读：家务管理也是狂野世界的一部分</a><br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-rabbit-hutch-tess-gunty/9780593534663?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>《兔子笼》</em></strong></a> <strong>，作者：苔丝·冈蒂</strong><br><br>阅读一本真正描绘了当地情况的书感觉有点像从家里旅行——你可以了解一个地方的历史、人民和细节的一切。甘蒂的处女作<em>《兔子笼》</em>就在这方面做出了贡献。这是一个多声部的故事，讲述了印第安纳州瓦卡谷 (Vacca Vale) 的低收入公寓 La Lapinière 的许多居民的故事，当地人将其称为“兔子小屋”。小说开始于 C4 公寓的青少年居民布兰丁·沃特金斯 (Blandine Watkins) 遭到袭击。她认为这种暴力是她身体的“出口”，这句话呼应了她对中世纪神秘主义者希尔德加德·冯·宾根的痴迷。小说从这里开始倒退，讲述了导致那一刻发生的原因，追踪了兔舍里不同的主人在七月炎热的一周里的生活：一位母亲最后告诉她，一位在线讣告评论版主让一位名人的儿子感到恼火，甚至到了危险的程度。她害怕丈夫的孩子的眼睛，而与布兰丁住在一起的三个年轻人也对她着迷。这是一次精彩的思考，探讨了我们对最近的邻居有多少不了解，以及我们居住的地方如何让我们走到一起，或者让我们分裂。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2022/08/book-recommendations-narrative-tools-setting/671216/">阅读：七本书，其中的背景暴露了人物</a><br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/possession-a-s-byatt/9780679735908?affiliate_id=atl-347"><strong><em>控球</em></strong></a><strong>，AS Byatt</strong><br><br>这可能感觉违反直觉，但当没有其他事情可以吸引我的注意力时，我知道是时候做多了。与我整天看到的文章、推文和 TikTok 不同，我发现一本结构和节奏冗长的长篇小说——尤其是在一段时间内深入探讨多种心理——总是能让我保持专注。很多经典小说都提供了这一点，但我最喜欢的是拜厄特的<em>《占有》</em> ，这是一部 1990 年的小说，采用维多利亚时代的结构，并赋予它后现代的倾向。有两条时间线——一条是当代叙事，其中学者罗兰·米歇尔和莫德·贝利发现了两位维多利亚时代诗人之间的信件，并重建了一段缺失的文学史；一条是维多利亚时代叙事，其中我们看到了同一位诗人伦道夫之间的关系。亨利·阿什和克里斯塔贝尔·拉莫特。这两个情节交织着诗歌、信件和学术书籍的摘录——所有这些都是拜厄特精心撰写的。这两个世界创造了强烈的戏剧性讽刺：读者可以看到米歇尔和贝利的正确之处，以及他们的档案永远无法捕捉到的东西，提醒我们过去的领域到底是多么未知。缓慢的节奏意味着我们可以深入研究每个观点，但这本书自始至终仍然令人兴奋，因为一幅历史的图画慢慢地映入眼帘。到最后，我发现我总是渴望再次开始阅读它。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 14:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/08/attention-focus-book-recommendations/674941/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/08/attention-focus-book-recommendations/674941/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Texas Is a Look Into the Future of Driving]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>无意识的能源消耗不再是现状。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/OZkBeEXMXgMU_90DVBnsEUdwp9I=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/cars_tx/original.jpg" alt="德克萨斯州高速公路上的汽车照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>艾莉莎·舒卡 / Redux</figcaption></figure>我认识的每个德克萨斯人都有所谓的“电网焦虑”，这是一种对电力的低沉关注，这种关注是在 2021 年 2 月残酷的冬季暴风雨摧毁了该州<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bakerinstitute.org/research/connecting-past-and-future-history-texas-isolated-power-grid">孤立的电网</a>后出现的。那场寒冷的灾难引发了高速公路连环相撞，杂货店停电；人们为了取暖而在室内开烤架和汽车，无意中一氧化碳<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/sections/live-updates-winter-storms-2021/2021/02/18/969050038/a-disaster-within-a-disaster-carbon-monoxide-poisoning-cases-are-surging-in-texa">中毒</a>。我的家乡圣安东尼奥，就像全州的许多地方一样，根本无法应对几天的冰冻温度。造成如此规模灾难的因素有很多，但该州能源基础设施的根本性失败怎么强调也不为过。<br><br>极端寒冷是这一范围的一端。今年夏天，德克萨斯州达到了另一个目标，破纪录的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/south-extreme-heat-wave-texas-climate-change/674598/">高温笼罩了南部</a>。现在，我与家乡人的交谈不可避免地会问：“你们的电网准备好了吗？”到目前为止，答案是肯定的，部分原因是该州可再生能源（尤其是太阳能）的大幅扩张。但能源并不简单：如果热浪发生得更频繁，额外的太阳能发电能力只能让我们走得更远，而且不利的天气或持续到夜间的高温可能会削弱太阳能发电能力。专家<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/solar-power-bails-out-texas-grid-during-major-heat-wave/">表示</a>，德克萨斯州的电网还没有为即将到来的极端气候变化做好准备。除此之外，还有另一个复杂的因素：德克萨斯人需要开车，而且越来越多的人开始驾驶<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.recurrentauto.com/research/texas-electric-vehicle-trends-stats">电动汽车</a>，而电动汽车以复杂的方式与电网互动。德克萨斯州现在是美国第三大电动汽车市场；自那场冬季暴风雪发生以来，注册数量至少增加了一倍， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.kxan.com/news/texas/texas-surpasses-200k-electric-vehicle-registrations-statewide/#:~:text=Last%20month%2C%20Gov.,most%20passenger%20vehicles%20and%20trucks.">如今已超过 20 万个</a>——所有这些都运行在从未设计用于为汽车提供动力的电力基础设施上。那么，德克萨斯人询问电网是否也能做到<em>这一点</em>是可以理解的。<br><br>尽管电动汽车承诺改善气候，但许多人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.kvue.com/article/news/investigations/defenders/electric-vehicles-texas-power-grid/269-e54f61e6-54dc-40a5-960a-776390736251">认为这些汽车只会吸收能量，直到耗尽能量</a>，就像大型电器整天运行一样，导致发电厂加班加点以进行补偿。一旦电池充满电，它们就会在极端温度下挣扎。 Recurrent 是一家为电动汽车买家提供电池健康状况报告的初创公司，其首席执行官兼联合创始人斯科特·凯斯 (Scott Case) 指出，当温度超过 100 度时，电动汽车的续航里程可能会减少约 30%。 “没有任何电池技术能够改变物理学，”他告诉我。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/tesla-charging-stations-ford-gm-nacs/674423/">阅读：特斯拉的魔力已归结于其充电器</a><br><br>考虑到这一点，德克萨斯州是未来的领头羊，随着我们对电动汽车的依赖不断增加，而气温却永久上升，我们中的许多人很快就会生活在这个未来。你可以想象噩梦般的场景：随着天气变得更糟，电动汽车成为电网的消耗者，导致大范围停电，然后耗尽的电池将汽车变成轮子上的砖头。如此戏剧性的未来可能不会实现，但我们将无法维持现状：更加极端的气候，加上电动汽车的相对复杂性，将要求驾驶员改变他们与能源消耗的关系，以及汽车与能源消耗的关系。制造商重新考虑他们生产什么以及如何生产。<br><br>总部位于德克萨斯州的电力巨头瑞致达对接下来的发展持乐观态度。该公司负责联邦和州宣传的高级经理艾米丽·斯蒂普(Emily Stipe)是随着热度变得更加极端而寻求缓解与电动汽车相关基础设施担忧的几位能源官员之一。斯蒂普在非营利组织零排放运输协会（ZETA）最近的一次演讲中表示：“我们确实相信电网将能够应对电动汽车的部署。”但这只有在多方共同努力的情况下才会发生，“不仅包括实际的电动汽车行业本身，还包括其供应链、电力供应商和消费者”。<br><br>大多数证据表明，电动汽车不会给电网带来人们想象的那么大压力。 ZETA 估计，到 2021 年，电动汽车仅消耗全国能源发电总量的 0.15%。该组织表示，可用能源的增长远远超过了电动汽车的新需求。德克萨斯州电力可靠性委员会的发言人表示，尽管德克萨斯州的销量稳步增长，但“目前，电动汽车的负载还不足以对电网产生影响”，该委员会负责运营该州 90% 的电网， 告诉我。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/jun/28/texas-heatwave-power-grid-solar-energy">据报道，自 2022 年以来，太阳能发电量翻了一番</a>，这也帮助该州老化的发电厂保持供电——尽管在石油和天然气占主导地位的地方<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.texastribune.org/2023/05/25/texas-energy-renewables-natural-gas-grid-politics/">，可再生能源遭到相当大的反对</a>。 （更环保的电网还可以帮助电动汽车发挥最大潜力，减少交通排放。）<br><br>电动汽车还可以提供许多人尚未意识到的好处。福特、现代、大众等公司的汽车正在设计将<a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://virta.global/vehicle-to-grid-v2g?__hstc=51530422.6ad426d1409f1436c8073dc60c9478b9.1690253826668.1690253826668.1690253826668.1&amp;__hssc=51530422.12.1690253826668&amp;__hsfp=2924083047&amp;hsutk=6ad426d1409f1436c8073dc60c9478b9&amp;contentType=standard-page&amp;pageId=19739738079#three">能量返回电网</a>，这种技术称为双向充电。虽然汽油车油箱中存储的潜在能量只能以一种方式使用，但这些电动汽车可以帮助家庭供电或将电力卖回电网。 “当你了解什么是电网弹性时，它实际上是电网准备和适应不断变化的运行条件的能力，”南加州爱迪生公司电气化总监香奈尔·帕森告诉我。她说，由于电动汽车一天中实际上只行驶了 5% 到 10% 的时间，因此“一天中剩下 21 到 23 个小时，汽车可以将电池放电给家庭甚至电网。”<br><br>这确实需要许多公用事业公司目前正在进行的“智能电网”升级，包括新的变压器、延长的电力线以及更好的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.smart-energy.com/digitalisation/cybersecurity/does-v2g-pose-a-cyber-threat-to-the-grid/">网络安全</a>。但是，在太阳能和风能较弱的日子里，电池存储有巨大的潜力可以提供帮助。斯蒂普告诉我，由于连接到电网的巨型电池，加利福尼亚州甚至在去年九月的热浪中避免了停电。通常，这些电池是对以前的电动汽车电池进行重新利用的。 “我们亲眼目睹了储能提供的许多好处，甚至超出了减排好处，”她说。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/05/where-are-the-ev-charging-stations/674241/">阅读：阻碍美国电动汽车发展的一件事</a><br><br>即使现在，大多数电动汽车都配备了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nrel.gov/transportation/managed-electric-vehicle-charging.html">智能充电</a>选项：能够通过汽车软件或充电器应用程序管理充电时间和电量。就像智能恒温器一样，电动汽车车主可以<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S8oASdb_CjQ">安排和管理非高峰时段的充电</a>。换句话说，您可以在晚上下班回家后插入电动汽车，但安排它在夜间充电，此时电网还没有因高温而过度工作，而且全家人都在家里用电。这也可以在公共充电器上完成。<br><br>当前电动汽车领域的世界领先者长期以来一直在玩这个游戏。特斯拉提供太阳能瓷砖和家庭储能解决方案，例如 Powerwall。现在许多“传统”汽车公司都在开发竞争产品。通用汽车公司的一个新部门通用汽车能源公司正在为家庭和企业推出所谓的“电动生态系统”，包括太阳能、充电、备用电池和双向充电技术。 “如果你能够管理能源、流入和流出，作为消费者，你可以对所有这些类型的产品进行管理，那么你就有机会帮助减轻恶劣环境带来的一些问题。天气，”通用汽车发言人小达里尔哈里森告诉我。这些功能预计将随着新款雪佛兰 Silverado EV 的零售发布而推出，该车型将于今年晚些时候开始生产。<br><br>持续的热浪时代也将改变电动汽车的制造方式。许多汽车制造商正在通过添加新的硬件功能（例如<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.moveelectric.com/e-cars/what-heat-pump-and-how-do-they-benefit-electric-cars">热泵）</a>来应对极端温度导致车辆行驶里程缩短的问题。凯斯说，虽然这些通常主要被视为冬季续航里程的好处，但它们释放暖空气的能力也可以大大提高夏季的续航里程。他说，与拥有电动汽车的许多其他现实一样，热泵的使用——包括监控能源使用情况和找出<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/06/electric-vehicle-rental-cars-hertz-chargers/674429/">最佳充电方式</a>——需要改变司机的行为，他们几十年来只是支付汽油费然后开车离开： “每个人在成长过程中都从父母或祖父母那里学习如何保养内燃机汽车。”在新生的电动汽车时代，“现在每个人都在制定新规则。”<br><br>也许更大的挑战将是让司机、房主甚至租房者开始以不同的方式思考他们的能源使用情况。无意识地消耗燃料或电力已不再是我们的奢侈品。 “对于许多人来说，他们只是希望在按下开关时灯就亮起来，除了每年的更新期之外，他们不想考虑他们的电力计划，”斯蒂普说。 “我们确实需要改变这一点。”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 13:25:07 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/electric-vehicle-energy-infrastruct-heat-waves/674940/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/08/electric-vehicle-energy-infrastruct-heat-waves/674940/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Three Attacks on Intellectual Freedom]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>国际笔会努力调和其对社会正义的承诺和对言论自由的承诺。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/RvB3J9O-G-0EMxFw0lNublu9a84=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/PENProtection/original.png" alt="带有盾牌引号气泡的雕像" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>保罗·斯佩拉/《大西洋月刊》插图； Source: Getty.</figcaption></figure> <small><em>Updated at 9:21 pm ET on August 7, 2023</em></small><br><br> <span class="smallcaps">1953 年 6 月</span>，在麦卡锡时代的鼎盛时期，国会调查人员和私人团体以国家安全、美国图书馆协会和协会图书出版商委员会的名义追捕“颠覆性”或仅仅是“令人反感的”书籍和作者发表了一份名为“阅读自由”的宣言。该文件捍卫言论自由，谴责审查制度和语言一致性，其清晰度和力度在今天令人震惊。它主张“观点和表达的最广泛多样性”，并反对基于“作者的个人历史或政治背景”的清洗工作。它敦促出版商和图书馆员抵制政府和私人压制，并“通过提供丰富思想质量和多样性的书籍，充分体现阅读自由”。该宣言不仅涉及官方审查制度，还涉及更广泛的胁迫和群体思维氛围。它的结论是：“我们提出这些主张并不是因为人们认为人们读到的内容并不重要。相反，我们相信人们阅读的内容非常重要；想法可能是危险的；但压制思想对于民主社会来说是致命的。自由本身是一种危险的生活方式，但它是我们的。”<br><br> “阅读自由”被报纸和电视新闻报道。同月，德怀特·艾森豪威尔总统敦促达特茅斯学院的毕业生不要“加入焚书者行列”，他给宣言的作者写了一封表扬信。在美国历史上最黑暗的时期之一，这份宣言给了图书馆员和出版商坚持其原则的勇气。一位图书管理员后来写道：“出现了一种战斗职业，由确信自己方向的奉献者组成。”<br><br>今年六月，图书馆和出版商协会在《自由阅读》成立 70 周年之际<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.slj.com/story/Freedom-to-Read-Statement-Reissued-on-Its-70th-Anniversary#:~:text=On%20the%2070th%20anniversary%20of,statement%20and%20reaffirmed%20its%20message.">重新发行了该书</a>。许多出版商、图书馆、文学团体、公民自由组织和作家签署了其原则。然而，许多机构签署者——包括“五巨头”出版集团——经常违反其主张，甚至可能没有意识到他们正在这样做。其中很少有人（如果有的话）能够像在审判者摧毁职业和生活的时代那样毫无歉意地捍卫知识自由。值得一问的是，为什么 2023 年的美国文坛比 1953 年的作家更无法坚持“阅读自由”的原则。<br><br>今天对知识自由的攻击来自多个方向。首先——这可能是签署者主要关心的——是州长、州立法机构、地方政府和学校董事会发起的一场官方运动，以清除他们不喜欢的书籍和想法。大多数目标在政治上属于左派；大多数内容呈现有关种族、性别和性的事实或表达观点，而审查者认为这些事实或观点是危险的、分裂的、淫秽的或完全错误的。这项努力早在 2020 年就在德克萨斯州开始，随后公众的歇斯底里和政治机会主义将这场运动蔓延到了佛罗里达州和其他州以及各级教育，从图书馆书架和课堂阅读清单上撤下了托妮·莫里森 (Toni Morrison) 等作家的数千本书。马拉拉·优素福扎伊。<br><br>鉴于州和学区有责任制定公立学校课程，并非所有这些都可以称为政府审查。但防止学生遇到有争议的、不受欢迎的、甚至冒犯性的作家和思想的法律和政策相当于一场强有力的禁书运动，其中一些可能违反宪法。这场运动源于美国的传统，即对快速变化和非正统思维的狭隘恐慌。您可以将田纳西州 1925 年的<em>Scopes</em>审判与佛罗里达州 2022 年的 Stop WOKE 法案划清界限。这种对知识自由的威胁是图书界占主导地位的进步和开明人士最容易反对的。企鹅兰登书屋或国家图书基金会的所有人都毫不犹豫地支持<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/05/01/books/maia-kobabe-gender-queer-book-ban.html"><em>《性别酷儿》</em></a>和<em>《使女的故事》</em> 。<br><br> “烧书的方法<span class="smallcaps">不止</span>一种，”雷·布拉德伯里曾经说过。 “世界上到处都是拿着点燃的火柴到处乱跑的人。”对知识自由的第二个威胁来自不同的来源——来自内部。这种威胁是美国笔会刚刚发布的一份新报告的主题，题为《<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pen.org/report/booklash">书荒：文学自由、网络愤怒和伤害语言</a>》。 （因为我过去<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/04/equity-language-guides-sierra-club-banned-words/673085/">写过有关审查制度和语言的文章</a>，笔会要求我阅读并回复早期的草稿，并给了我一份最终版本的预发副本。）该报告重点关注出版商和作者取消其出版商和作者的最新模式。自己的书，有时是在出版后，在网上或由自己的员工（通常是年轻人）组织的压力下。自 2016 年以来，国际笔会追踪了 31 起可能被称为文学杀婴的案件；一半发生在过去两年内。报告指出：“这些书都没有因为任何关于事实虚假信息、美化暴力或抄袭的指控而被撤回。” “他们的内容或作者只是被认为具有攻击性。”<br><br>一些案例成了大新闻。阿歇特公司在员工罢工后取消了伍迪·艾伦的自传，布莱克·贝利的菲利普·罗斯传记在诺顿出版后被撤回，两者都是在作者指控不当性行为之后（艾伦和贝利否认了这些指控）。出版商在某位作者发表公开言论后取消了书籍——例如漫画家斯科特·亚当斯、英国记者朱莉·伯奇尔和右翼煽动者米洛·扬诺普洛斯的书籍。<br><br>在一个特别疯狂的案例中，一位名叫娜塔莎·泰恩斯的作家在即将出版她的第一部犯罪惊悚小说的同时，看到华盛顿特区地铁系统的一名黑人雇员在火车上吃东西（违反了该系统的规则）。她在推特上发布了一张该女子在交通局的照片并提出投诉，但立即发现自己变成了一名病毒式的种族主义者。几个小时后，她的发行商稀有鸟类图书公司就放弃了这本小说，并在推特上称泰恩斯“今天做了一件非常可怕的事情”。出版商加州冷血 (California Coldblood) 在试图放弃这本书之后，最终“由于合同义务”继续出版，但这本小说就等于死了。 “你怎么能指望作家成为从不犯任何错误的完美生物呢？”泰恩斯向笔会哀叹。现在，大多数出版商都在图书合同中加入了道德条款，使这些取消合法化——这一漏洞与这些出版商所认可的“阅读自由”的原则相矛盾。<br><br>报告中讨论的许多案例与作者的攻击性言论或不良行为无关。相反，它们涉及措辞、人物塑造、情节、主题或作者身份的错误。去年，皮卡多出版社放弃了一位教师的获奖回忆录，因为该回忆录因对种族不敏感的描述而受到攻击。在批评者指出其作者​​是白人后，维普夫和斯托克撤回了一项关于黑人女权主义文化的学术研究。西蒙与舒斯特因希特勒而抢先杀掉了一本为希特勒儿童写的传记。四本青少年和儿童小说（似乎特别容易受到攻击）因涉嫌令人反感的故事和描述而被下架。其中一本名为<em>《狼群之地》（A Place for Wolves</em> ）的小说，讲述了两名美国同性恋男孩在与塞尔维亚的战争期间发生在科索沃的故事。在社交媒体上的人们指责他之后，该书的作者科索科·杰克逊（Kosoko Jackson）被取消了。科索科·杰克逊本人也是通过 Twitter 进行文学犯罪的检察官。他违反了自己关于身份的法令，对适当的主题进行了严格限制：“有关民权运动的故事应该由黑人撰写，”他在推特上写道。 “选举权的故事应该由女性来书写。因此，关于男孩在可怕和改变生活的时代（如艾滋病流行）的故事应该由男同性恋者来写。为什么这么难得到？”<br><br>这些文学“autos-da-fé”的核心是身份——或者用报告多次使用的一句话来说，“边缘化身份”。可能毁掉作家作品的绊脚石——对“有害”语言的指控、“再现”失败、“挪用”或普遍存在“问题”内容的指控——全都是沿着身份线串起来的。 2020 年，当白人作家珍妮·康明斯 (Jeanine Cummins) 因小说<em>《美国污垢》(American Dirt</em> ) 受到广泛关注（据报道还获得了七位数的图书交易）时，该小说讲述了墨西哥母子逃离贩毒团伙的故事。一些评论家说，本应属于拉丁裔作家的机会，他本可以写出一本更好的书。她的出版商熨斗/麦克米伦没有撤下这本小说——它的销量太多了——但它以安全问题为由取消了康明斯的巡演，并发表了一份卑鄙的自我批评声明。 <em>《美国污垢》</em>的磨难向出版商表明，跨越身份界限可能是危险的，这促使一位接受笔会匿名采访的前编辑问道：“我们是说不是任何人都可以写故事吗？你必须有一定的身份吗？对此有很多恐惧。”<br><br>怀疑论者可能会问，为什么每年出版的数万本书中的几十个尴尬的决定和小争议会很重要。答案是，这些事件揭示了一种从众和恐惧的氛围，这种氛围削弱了图书出版不仅仅是一项业务的主张。报告中描述的大多数被取消的书籍都是普遍正统观念的受害者。在最严格的情况下，这种正统观念将身份的主张置于一切之上——文学质量、作者独立性、阅读自由。它的影响力可以从许多被取消的书籍中明显看出，尽管笨拙，但努力遵守公平和包容的价值观；娜塔莎·泰恩斯（Natasha Tynes）试图通过辩称自己是“少数族裔作家”来保护自己免受网络攻击。<br><br>最终，正统观念使得对书籍的压制变得不必要，因为它会导致编辑和作家的自我审查。一位被取消资格的作家在接受国际笔会采访时表示：“这让我在创造性上失去了兴趣。总有一个审查员站在我的肩膀上，告诉我不能写这个或那个话题。”哪个作家能诚实地说这不是真的？几乎没有一位接受笔会报告采访的编辑愿意被提及姓名。如果他们害怕的不是作者的命运，他们还害怕什么呢？<br><br>水线以下是所有未签约的书籍，甚至是未编写的书籍，因为这些例子已被公开。畅销书作家理查德·诺斯·帕特森 (Richard North Patterson) 在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-my-new-novel-about-racial-conflict-ran-into-trouble-53a53f54"><em>《华尔街日报》的</em></a>一篇<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-my-new-novel-about-racial-conflict-ran-into-trouble-53a53f54">专栏文章</a>中写道，他的最新小说——讲述了反对投票权和白人种族主义之争的跨种族关系——被“大约 20 家”纽约出版商拒绝。帕特森写道：“似乎占主导地位的情绪是，只有那些个人受到歧视的人才能安全地通过虚构人物来描述歧视。” （ <em>《审判》</em>由田纳西州一家保守的基督教公司于 6 月出版，目前在亚马逊所有图书中排名第 37,000 名左右。笔会报告中的几本书被主要出版商取消，被影响力小得多的小出版社抢走了。）<br><br> PEN 是一个言论自由组织。在已经发布了一份<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pen.org/report/banned-usa-growing-movement-to-censor-books-in-schools/">冗长的报告</a>和大量声明谴责州和地方政府禁书之后，它似乎已经意识到，它不能忽视国内笔会成员出版和赞助其筹款晚会的组织的镇压模式。<br><br> 5月，国际笔会陷入了自己的言论自由争议，两名乌克兰士兵作家宣布，如果两名俄罗斯作家也加入另一个小组，他们将退出该组织的世界之声节。国际笔会没有取消已经抵达美国的乌克兰人，并将他们送回国内参加战争，而是要求俄罗斯作家及其小组主持人、国际笔会董事会成员玛莎·格森以不同的旗帜发言，美国笔会。相反，俄罗斯人和格森决定取消自己的活动，格森辞去董事会职务，以抗议国际笔会屈服于乌克兰人的要求。 （一位俄罗斯作家后来说，如果乌克兰人不希望她在那里，她就不想参加。）一个月后，当作家伊丽莎白·吉尔伯特暂停出版她的下一篇作品时，国际笔会宣称这是“令人遗憾的”和“错误的”。小说是因为乌克兰读者对它以苏联为背景感到不安。所有这一切仅仅表明，当你不是面临不愉快后果的人时，在言论自由问题上坚持原则立场会更容易。<br><br>国际笔会花了几个月的时间研究和内部辩论这份新报告，预计会引起争议。早期的草稿受到了反身性的限制和策略性批评的阻碍，其中一些仍保留在已发表的报告中：对文学伤害的指控“有可能落入右翼书籍横幅的手中”，他们使用同样的言辞；如果<em>《美国污垢》</em>的出版商更加敏感地推销这部小说，也许可以避免麻烦。<br><br>在我们这个时代，这份报告是一份重要的、甚至是勇敢的文件。国际笔会正在为图书行业提供指导和支柱，而图书行业在不断的愤怒面前似乎失去了勇气并忘记了自己的使命。在其建议中，报告敦促“出版社应该很少（如果有的话）将书籍从流通中撤回。”它呼吁提高透明度并让作者参与任何有关取消的决定。 Goodreads 是一个在线书评网站， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/goodreads-review-bombing-amazon-moderation/674811/">有时暴徒们甚至在书还没读完之前就把书打死</a>，更不用说出版和阅读了，它被要求“鼓励真实的书评”并防止“书评轰炸”。<br><br>这些技术修复将极大地改善出版业的政策和程序，但它们无法解决更广泛的问题——窒息图书世界的不宽容和怯懦气氛。国际笔会在其报告的结论中呼吁“文学话语中更广泛的基调转变”，这是必要的，但可能超出了任何报告的力量。本质上，笔会是在对剩下的看门人说：“记住你的目的”，并对新的闯入者说：“不要用言论来限制言论。”为了寻求灵感，它全文转载了《阅读的自由》，并敦促图书界的工作者牢记它。美国笔会 (PEN America) 主席阿亚德·阿赫塔尔 (Ayad Akhtar) 告诉我，他希望出版商将这份 70 年前的宣言与新员工的 DEI 培训一起纳入其中。国际笔会希望其报告能够产生与之前文件类似的效果——让出版业再次成为“战斗职业”。<br><br>然而，有些因素阻碍了该报告使用“阅读自由”的豪言壮语<em>。</em>我认为困难在于笔会去年发表的一份较早的报告。<br><br>在《言外之意：种族、公平和图书出版》一书中，美国笔会详细研究了美国图书业的现状，尽管最近有所改善，但仍然是一个白人、人脉广泛、富裕的俱乐部世界。它展示了一幅有数据支撑的可怕图景，即“作家、编辑和出版商通过白色镜头来策划美国文学”。它呼吁出版商雇用和提拔更多的有色人种员工，出版更多有色人种作家的书籍，向他们支付更高的预付款，并更明智、更积极地销售他们的书籍。<br><br>这两份报告是相关的，但其关系却令人担忧。第一个表明需要加强整个行业的多样性、公平性和包容性运动。第二个观点主张有更大的自由来挑战多样性、公平性和包容性的文学限制。两者之间有矛盾吗？<br><br>笔会不这么认为。新报告指出：“文学领域必须制定一条促进多样性和公平性的路线，而不是让这些价值观成为对那些被认为在这些领域达不到要求的特定书籍或作家的打击。” In the words of Suzanne Nossel, PEN&#39;s chief executive officer, “You can dismantle the barriers to publication for some without erecting them anew for others.”但这可能是一厢情愿的想法，不仅因为可以出版的书籍数量受到实际限制。在另一个世界中，完全有可能在不营造挑剔氛围的情况下扩大机会。在我们的世界里，DEI 已经成为一种意识形态的试金石，将社会正义置于出版中心的努力几乎不可避免地会引发关于“代表性”和“伤害”的争议，从而导致书籍被禁。第一份报告将出版中的 DEI 视为一项紧迫的道德事业。第二份报告对“员工越来越期望出版商在目录和作者名单的管理中承担道德立场”提出了质疑。但这些员工无疑相信他们正在实现第一份报告的愿景。<br><br>社会正义和知识自由本质上并不对立——通常，两者都需要对方——但它们也不是同一件事。 《阅读自由》明确指出：“[出版商和图书馆员]建立自己的政治、道德或美学观点作为决定应该出版或发行什么的标准，这将与公共利益发生冲突。”该声明是在知识自由的事业是非意识形态甚至是反意识形态的时代写下的。其作者主张的目标就是最广泛和最高质量的观点表达。但在国际笔会的新报告中，你会感到很难调和其早期报告的思想，其中每一个计算都归结为身份，以及对创作文学至关重要的歧视性判断和对新的、令人不安的想法的开放态度。正如一位编辑告诉我的那样，“人才是不公平的。”<br><br>去年，一位联邦法官阻止了美国最大出版商企鹅兰登书屋收购第三大出版商西蒙与舒斯特公司的出价（收购实际上将使该集团成为一个主权国家）。今年，全行业图书销量下滑，带来裁员潮；上个月，企鹅兰登书屋的高级编辑在解约的阴影下获得了买断的选择，出版界一些最杰出的把关人也纷纷离职。这些事件让我想到了对书面文字的第三次也是最严重的攻击。<br><br>与图书禁令和取消相比，这一问题更加阴险和普遍，因此更难以清楚地看到，更不用说反对了。这是每个作家和读者呼吸的空气：出版业被整合为近乎垄断的行业；异端观念和冒险行为相应减少；员工经济状况脆弱；书店和书评的衰落；公众文盲率不断上升；无论政治压力如何，学校的英语教学都在下降；数据处理将想法转化为机器制造的产品，将媒体转化为高度敏感的流行晴雨表（人工智能即将取代人类原创性的最后痕迹）。所有这些趋势都构成了对自由知识的攻击，这种攻击不是由 Moms for Liberty 或 YA Twitter 发起的，而是由马克·扎克伯格 (Mark Zuckerberg)、华纳兄弟探索频道 (Warner Bros. Discovery) 和亚马逊发起的。从某种意义上说，第三次攻击是其他两次攻击的基础，因为强烈的情感和极端的语言被算法编入各种类型的书籍横幅的大脑中，这些算法使少数技术和媒体巨头受益。<br><br>文学和新闻从来都不是高薪领域。但与三十年前相比，今天从事认真、持续的职业生涯的机会要小得多。我不禁想到，这些情况与出版商愿意被几百条推文吓倒有关。也许多年的整合和不稳定已经削弱了他们对图书出版使命的信念，以至于网上和内部的一点愤怒就足以消除这种信念。如果编辑的作用是匹配作者的身份和主题，然后收集数据来衡量产品的成功，也许看门人终于失去了用处。<br><br> <em><small>This article previously misstated Suzanne Nossel&#39;s title at PEN America.</small></em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 11:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/freedom-to-read-pen-america-censorship/674936/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/freedom-to-read-pen-america-censorship/674936/</item><item><title><![CDATA[The Burden of Proof Is on the Language Police]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>关于特定术语伤害他人的说法应该以严格的方式进行评估，而不仅仅是基于直觉。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Yh_Ri7MpSMGvKtZxMP9uBhVAl9Q=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/language_horz_1/original.jpg" alt="由铁丝网制成的语音气泡的插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。 Source: Getty.</figcaption></figure>在我作为科学期刊的高级编辑的工作中，我在审稿人、作者、其他编辑和读者之间调解的最具挑战性的论点不是关于研究方法、经验数据或微妙的理论观点，而是关于描述弱势群体的术语哪些是可以接受的，哪些是有害的。我的领域——毒瘾和毒品政策——有着围绕语言展开野蛮内讧的传统。那些被前几代人嘲笑为<i>流浪者</i>或<i>流浪汉</i>的人，更恰当的称呼是<i>无家可归的人</i>、无家可归<i>的人</i><i>、</i>无家可归<i>的人、有过无家可归经历的人</i>，还是其他什么？类似的争论也爆发在政治、新闻、课堂、工作场所以及餐桌上的几代人之间。当即使是真诚、善意的人也无法就哪些词语加剧社会不公正、损害人类福祉达成一致时，争论可能会导致双方互相伤害。<br><br>有时，随着时间的推移，争论会自行解决，而诸如<i>“瘾君子”</i>和<i>“瘾君子”</i>之类明显带有贬义的词语也会从公众话语中消失得无影无踪。值得赞扬的是，研究和治疗成瘾的学者敏锐地意识到负面语言如何向公众灌输负面态度，从而使公共政策针对吸毒和酗酒障碍患者。也就是说，任何有关特定术语具有积极危害性的主张在被确定为事实之前都应被视为假设。当面对“ <i>X”</i>一词对具有特定特征的人造成伤害，或者“ <i>Y”</i>一词是尊重他们的唯一方式的说法时，一个公正的人可以合理地回答：“什么证据表明这是真的？”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/07/brandeis-language-police-have-suggestions-you/619347/">约翰·麦克沃特（John McWhorter）：现在甚至<i>连触发警告</i>也被禁止</a><br><br>可以肯定的是，当某人明确表达了他或她希望如何被描述的偏好时，这种愿望不需要证据验证。在某些情况下，尊重他人的自我认知可能意味着容忍善意的局外人认为生硬、不礼貌甚至具有破坏性的语言。例如， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/all-about-addiction/201809/never-call-someone-alcoholic-or-addict">我所在领域的一些成员认为，</a>康复中的人不应该用<i>“瘾君子</i>”和<i>“酗酒者</i>”这些词来加重自己的负担——这些词很可能会在未经他们同意的情况下对任何被贴上这样标签的人造成侮辱，但“12步计划”的参与者广泛声称这些词。科学家和临床医生必须尊重他人的人性，其中包括维护他们发言和定义自己的权利。<br><br>当一个术语被断言有害时索要证据会让一些人觉得这仅仅是对变革的抵制。事实上，有大量关于术语影响的证据可以指导我们，并且在某些情况下，它支持语言的转变。根据我所在领域的一项研究，看到一个人被描述为<i>药物滥用者</i>而不是<i>患有</i><i>药物使用障碍，</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/002204261004000403">会让人们更有可能将其视为安全威胁并应该受到惩罚</a>。有些术语被称为有害术语，因为它们显然就是有害的。<br><br>但许多其他关于个别术语的有害性或优点的主张缺乏明确的证据，因此我们应该谦虚地进行概括。专家和政策制定者为何应该容忍广泛的术语的最佳证据是，人们所喜欢的称呼具有多样性。有一天，一位美国白人同事批评我在讨论医疗保险参与者的药物过量问题时使用了据称有辱人格的术语<i>“长者</i>”，就在我接到 Zoom 电话会议之前不久，原住民血统的加拿大同事反复使用同一个术语来表示尊重他们社区中最长寿的成员。在我作为心理学家的临床培训期间，我被告知（没有证据）“<i>病人”</i>是一个具有破坏性的医学术语，指的是寻求心理健康护理的人，我应该只使用<i>“客户”</i> 。但对现实生活中寻求护理的人的调查并未达成共识。例如，在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://uhra.herts.ac.uk/handle/2299/5733">一项研究</a>中，看精神科医生或护士的人更喜欢<i>患者</i>，而<i>患者</i>和<i>客户</i>在咨询社会工作者或职业治疗师的人中同样受欢迎。对其他术语（包括<i>服务用户</i>、<i>使用服务的人和</i><i>消费者</i>）的接受程度差异很大。简而言之，不存在单一的理想术语，而对一个理想术语的寻找却以这样的现实为基础：具有相同条件的个体通常对于他们希望被称为什么而存在差异。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/04/equity-language-guides-sierra-club-banned-words/673085/">摘自 2023 年 4 月号：反对公平语言的道德案例</a><br><br>讽刺的是，通过新术语促进公平的冲动在某些情况下未能考虑到个人和文化多样性。许多美国学者很快就采用了<i>“拉丁裔”</i>这个新词，作为比<i>“西班牙裔</i>”或<i>“拉丁裔”</i>更具包容性、更中性的替代词，尽管这个词让一些拉丁美洲裔人感到困惑或恼火，而且<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/hispanic/2020/08/11/about-one-in-four-u-s-hispanics-have-heard-of-latinx-but-just-3-use-it/">调查数据</a>表明很少有人用它来描述自己。其他旨在减少社会耻辱的语言的影响并不总是很明显。在美国，<i>无家可归者</i>在某些方面已经声名狼藉，但没有可靠住所的人们是否受益于或更愿意使用表面上更平等的<i>无家可归者</i>或<i>无家可归者</i>，仍有待证明。良好的意图有时会产生大量术语，这些术语很快就会分解为首字母缩略词。<i>患有酒精使用障碍的人</i>可能具有一些人性化的潜力，但是否像许多学术论文那样将这个术语缩写为<i>PWAUD</i>具有预期的效果还只是一个猜测。<br><br>谴责别人的术语有害，并要求别人采用你自己的术语，可能会令人陶醉，以至于将此类争议提交给实证检验可能会让人感觉有点沮丧。 But making these judgments in a rigorous, fact-based way would prevent experts, policy makers, and the general public from being distracted by something easy—arguing about words—when we need to focus on doing something much harder: solving massive social problems. A shared commitment to evidence provides a way to resolve upsetting disagreements that can otherwise fester forever, while opening up chances to learn when we have in fact caused harm and genuinely need to treat others better.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/addiction-drug-policy-language-harm-evidence/674907/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/addiction-drug-policy-language-harm-evidence/674907/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Here Comes the Second Year of AI College]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Universities still aren&#39;t sure whether to embrace the technology or ban it. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/4lFQlZq-m5haSSvNy5GZSNgvFeM=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/08/ai_college_2/original.jpg" alt="An old-school computer-generated image of a graduation cap" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Joanne Imperio / The Atlantic</figcaption></figure> W <span class="smallcaps">hen ChatGPT entered the world</span> last fall, the faculty at SUNY Buffalo freaked out. Kelly Ahuna, the university&#39;s director of academic integrity, was inundated by panicked emails. “It has me thinking about retiring,” one English professor confessed. He had typed a prompt into ChatGPT and watched in horror as an essay unfurled on-screen. There were errors, sure: incorrect citations, weird transitions. But he would have given it a B-minus. He anticipated an onslaught of undetectable AI plagiarism. Ahuna found herself as something of a spiritual mentor, guiding faculty through their existential angst about artificial intelligence.<br><br> The first year of AI college was marked by <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/05/chatbot-cheating-college-campuses/674073/">mayhem and mistrust</a> . Educational institutions, accustomed to moving very slowly, for the most part failed to issue clear guidance. In this vacuum, professors grew suspicious of students who turned in particularly grammatical essays. Plagiarism detectors flagged legitimate work as AI-generated. Over the summer, some universities and colleges have regrouped; they&#39;re trying to embrace AI at the institutional level, incorporating it into curriculum and helping instructors adapt. But the norm is still to let individual educators fend for themselves—and some of those individuals seem to believe that they can keep teaching as if generative AI didn&#39;t exist.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/05/chatbot-cheating-college-campuses/674073/">Read: The first year of AI college ends in ruin</a><br><br> Modernizing higher education is a formidable task. I graduated from college this past spring. Before the pandemic, my professors insisted that we print assignments out and hand them in—forget submitting online. Although ChatGPT was available for nearly my entire senior year, the university administration sent out only one announcement about it, encouraging faculty to understand the implications of the technology. My friends, meanwhile, talked incessantly about it. I don&#39;t know anyone who wrote an entire paper with ChatGPT—or who would admit to it, at least—but people used it in other ways. Some asked it to generate practice-exam questions for them to solve. Others turned to it for help with their philosophy reading, asking the chatbot to explain, say, Parfit&#39;s definition of a self-effacing theory. One of my friends asked ChatGPT how to get over her ex-boyfriend. (The advice was generic but excellent.) But only one of my professors ever mentioned it: Halfway through the spring semester, my computer-science professor announced that we couldn&#39;t use ChatGPT to complete our codes. Then he said he would rely on the honor system.<br><br> Heading into the second year of AI college, some institutions are trying to develop a less technophobic approach. According to Kathe Pelletier, a director at the tech-focused education nonprofit Educause, the most enthusiastic AI adopters tend to be public universities or community colleges that serve large, diverse student bodies and see education as a means of social mobility. Arizona State University is piloting an introductory writing course in which an AI bot offers feedback on students&#39; work. The class is taught to remote learners at a low cost, and the AI could allow for something like peer feedback for students who take classes alone, on their own schedule. Administrators at the University of Tennessee at Knoxville have organized a professor-led task force to suggest different ways for faculty to add generative AI to the classroom. The University of Florida launched a $70 million AI initiative in 2020 with funding from the chip-manufacturing giant Nvidia. Sid Dobrin, an English professor who is part of the initiative, says that it will sponsor a competition this year in which students can win prize money for the most creative use of generative text or image AI. These schools are preparing to feed employers&#39; hunger for AI-savvy graduates. “I always say: You are not going to lose your job to AI,” Dobrin told me. “You are going to lose your job to somebody who understands how to use AI.”<br><br> Other universities, however, still have no overarching institutional posture toward AI. Administrators are wary of announcing policies that could age poorly. Professors are left to figure out how to leverage the technology on their own. In its defense, this stance preserves academic autonomy and encourages experimentation. For example, the teacher of Harvard&#39;s introductory computer-science course deployed a teaching-assistant chatbot this summer built based on OpenAI&#39;s code. But the hands-off institutional approach also forces instructors, many of whom have yet to master the “Mute” button on Zoom, to be at the vanguard of a technology that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/09/sam-altman-openai-chatgpt-gpt-4/674764/">isn&#39;t fully understood</a> even by the people who created it. In a recent informal <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://er.educause.edu/articles/2023/4/educause-quickpoll-results-adopting-and-adapting-to-generative-ai-in-higher-ed-tech">poll</a> by Educause, 40 percent of respondents said that they weren&#39;t aware of anyone at their institution taking responsibility for decisions around how generative AI should be used. “A president or provost is thinking, <em>Should I jump on this only to have it become the most unpopular thing in the world?</em> ” Bryan Alexander, who teaches at Georgetown University&#39;s school of learning, design, and technology, says.<br><br> Some academics have been eager to add the alien technology to their classroom. Ted Underwood, who teaches English and information science at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, says that every student should learn the basics of AI ethics. He likens the topic to the tenets of democracy, which even people who won&#39;t pursue political science need to understand. Other professors see AI as a way to enliven instruction. The new introductory writing course at the University of Utah asks students to compare sonnets written by William Shakespeare, Pablo Neruda, and ChatGPT; professors say that using an AI bot is the easiest way to generate usefully bad poems.<br><br> Another faction within academia sees generative AI as an enemy. In the age of large language models, a student&#39;s writing assignment can no longer reliably confirm whether they&#39;ve understood a topic or read a text. Weekly reading responses and discussion posts, once a staple of higher education, seem useless. Some instructors are trying to adopt countermeasures. One SUNY Buffalo faculty member told Kelly Ahuna that he would keep his weekly online quizzes but employ technology that tracks students&#39; eye movements to detect potential cheating. Others seem to hope that prohibition alone can preserve the familiar pre-ChatGPT world. Most instructors at Bryn Mawr College have declared that any use of AI tools counts as plagiarism, says Carlee Warfield, the head of the school&#39;s honor board. Darren Hick, a philosophy professor at Furman University, told me he refuses to abandon take-home essays. In his view, in-person exams aren&#39;t real philosophy. They leave no time for rumination and serious engagement with a thinker&#39;s work. “It&#39;s gimmicky,” Hick said. “My pedagogy is good, my students learn, and I don&#39;t like the idea of having to upend what&#39;s been a tradition in philosophy for millennia because somebody has a new technology that students can use to cheat.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2022/12/chatgpt-ai-writing-college-student-essays/672371/">Read: The college essay is dead</a><br><br> Many of the professors and administrators I spoke with likened generative AI to earlier waves of technological change; perhaps an analogy offered perspective and solace when confronting something so mystifying. They compared it to Wikipedia (riddled with inaccuracies), to calculators (students still learn long division), and even to microwave dinners (ChatGPT&#39;s writing is a frozen meat loaf; a student essay is a marbled steak).<br><br> But the most common comparison was to the advent of the internet. Charles Isbell, the dean of computing at Georgia Tech, points out that the web did not immediately create the kind of nightmarish scenario that people had predicted. Supersonic email exchanges didn&#39;t <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://edition.cnn.com/2005/WORLD/europe/04/22/text.iq/">scramble our brains</a> , just as the “Undo” button hasn&#39;t <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.zdnet.com/article/humanity-has-always-feared-technology-in-the-21st-century-are-we-right-to-be-afraid/">eroded our sense of consequence</a> . For now, Isbell isn&#39;t concerned about students cheating with AI: If they submit a ChatGPT-written essay, the errors will give them away, and if they try to avoid detection by meticulously fact-checking the chatbot&#39;s writing, they&#39;ll learn the material. But just like the internet, which spawned smartphones and social-media sites that few people could have foreseen, AI will undercut the most basic patterns in higher education. “It&#39;s perfectly reasonable to hold in your head both thoughts,” Isbell told me. “It&#39;s not going to be the big, destructive force that we think it&#39;s going to be anytime soon. Also, higher education will be completely unrecognizable in 15 years because of this technology. We just don&#39;t really know how.”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/ai-chatgpt-college-essay-plagiarism/674928/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/08/ai-chatgpt-college-essay-plagiarism/674928/</item></channel></rss>